WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.748 --> 00:00:06.080
Harvard invented
college reunions.

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:09.640
The first reunion
took place in 1643,

00:00:09.640 --> 00:00:12.520
a year after the first
commencement, when alumni

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:16.570
were invited back to celebrate
with the new graduates.

00:00:16.570 --> 00:00:20.210
During Harvard's
bicentennial year of 1636,

00:00:20.210 --> 00:00:23.940
the alumni festivities were
particularly exuberant.

00:00:23.940 --> 00:00:28.500
Ralph Waldo Emerson of
the Harvard class of 1821

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:32.635
wrote about the annual Harvard
alumni parade on that day

00:00:32.635 --> 00:00:34.990
in July of 1836.

00:00:34.990 --> 00:00:38.110
Here is what he
wrote in his journal.

00:00:38.110 --> 00:00:42.640
"Cambridge at anytime is full
of ghosts, but on that day

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:46.340
the anointed eye saw
the crowd of spirits

00:00:46.340 --> 00:00:49.410
that mingled with the
procession in the vacant spaces

00:00:49.410 --> 00:00:52.620
year by year as the
classes proceeded,

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:55.310
and then the far
longer train of ghosts

00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:57.660
that followed the
company of the men that

00:00:57.660 --> 00:00:59.740
wore before us
the college honors

00:00:59.740 --> 00:01:02.780
and the laurels of the
state, the long winding

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:05.880
train reaching back
into eternity."

00:01:05.880 --> 00:01:08.320
And you can hear in the
background the Harvard band

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:12.550
playing, and the long
winding train of alumni

00:01:12.550 --> 00:01:15.830
is forming in Harvard yard.

00:01:15.830 --> 00:01:18.020
Rennie, maybe you
can tell us what

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:20.690
we can expect to
hear this afternoon.

00:01:20.690 --> 00:01:22.290
Thank you, Nancy.

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:25.800
Nancy noted that she graduated
from the college in 1976

00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:30.320
and received her MBA from
Harvard Business School in '78.

00:01:30.320 --> 00:01:32.242
She has been a member
of the Committee

00:01:32.242 --> 00:01:33.950
for the Happy Observance
of Commencements

00:01:33.950 --> 00:01:36.750
for over 20 years now and
is currently the Alumni

00:01:36.750 --> 00:01:38.960
Association's treasurer.

00:01:38.960 --> 00:01:41.430
I believe that this is
her eighth year doing

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:44.320
this broadcasting in
the afternoon exercises.

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:47.045
So it's a pleasure to join you,
Nancy, high above courtside

00:01:47.045 --> 00:01:51.890
here as Johnny Most used to
say before the Celtics games.

00:01:51.890 --> 00:01:55.605
In our case, we have three steps
up in what is called the tree

00:01:55.605 --> 00:02:01.430
house on the stage left here
in the Tercentenary Theatre.

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:05.590
And I'd also like to
take the opportunity

00:02:05.590 --> 00:02:07.710
to thank Rachel Lamson,
Director of Board

00:02:07.710 --> 00:02:09.840
Services for the
Alumni Association,

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:13.140
and her assistant Kate
Freed who has put together

00:02:13.140 --> 00:02:16.080
a thick syllabus for us today.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:18.360
I also want to thank Diane
MacDonald and Deborah

00:02:18.360 --> 00:02:21.265
Smullyan in the Alumni
Association's Class Reports

00:02:21.265 --> 00:02:25.560
Office for providing information
on the fours and nines, which

00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:28.540
are the classes that are
reunioning this week.

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.100
Finally, I want to
thank our camera

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:32.920
crew, Kathy O'Connell,
Bob [? De Maison, ?]

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:35.910
and Ed McNamara for
the nice job that they

00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:39.510
do with keeping us all
in line and showing off

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:42.340
this wonderful event.

00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:45.680
We're going to see today
the afternoon exercises

00:02:45.680 --> 00:02:50.820
of commencement, robe
after robes scattered

00:02:50.820 --> 00:02:55.060
a rainbow, robes after robes
scattering the rainbow,

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:57.130
as David McCord said.

00:02:57.130 --> 00:02:59.330
Although we don't see as
many of those in robes

00:02:59.330 --> 00:03:01.720
this afternoon as
we see the alumni,

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:05.590
as this is the annual meeting
of the Alumni Association.

00:03:05.590 --> 00:03:08.780
And this is the fourth meeting
of the Alumni Association.

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:12.355
They hold three per year in
the fall, winter, and spring

00:03:12.355 --> 00:03:16.270
and then finish up with the
annual Alumni Association,

00:03:16.270 --> 00:03:19.998
which we are commencing today.

00:03:19.998 --> 00:03:24.060
The dignitaries are
just coming around.

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:26.940
They've already been
started off with the band.

00:03:26.940 --> 00:03:30.860
They are led off by the Chief
Marshal and his aids, Richard

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:34.580
Barth, who is the Chief
Marshal for commencement.

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:37.220
He is of the 25th
reunion class, but he

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:41.610
was elected by his
classmates in the fall.

00:03:41.610 --> 00:03:43.950
Both Nancy and I have
chaired that committee

00:03:43.950 --> 00:03:45.720
at one time or another.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:47.710
And it's the best
and the brightest

00:03:47.710 --> 00:03:51.720
from the class that are chosen.

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:53.470
There are usually eight
or nine candidates

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:56.645
selected by the class and
voted on by class members.

00:03:56.645 --> 00:04:02.350
The Chief Marshal appoints
alumni to assist the Committee

00:04:02.350 --> 00:04:04.750
for the Happy Observance
of Commencements

00:04:04.750 --> 00:04:08.450
and with such activities
as crowd management,

00:04:08.450 --> 00:04:12.520
the general alumni spread,
the tree spread for college

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:15.050
graduates who have had
their 50th reunion,

00:04:15.050 --> 00:04:19.380
and the Chief Marshal spread for
distinguished guests, honorans,

00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:22.160
family, and faculty.

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:26.140
Richard Barth, class of '89,
is the CEO of KIPP Foundation,

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:29.270
as Nancy mentioned,
Knowledge and Power

00:04:29.270 --> 00:04:31.910
Program, a network of schools.

00:04:31.910 --> 00:04:34.950
KIPP has grown to 141
schools, serving over

00:04:34.950 --> 00:04:37.780
50,000 students
across the country

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:39.470
in communities
where roughly half

00:04:39.470 --> 00:04:43.050
of the students drop out of
high school and only one in 10

00:04:43.050 --> 00:04:45.490
will earn a college degree.

00:04:45.490 --> 00:04:51.030
Among KIPP students, 95% of whom
are African American or Latino

00:04:51.030 --> 00:04:56.470
and 86% of whom are
low-income families, 93%

00:04:56.470 --> 00:05:03.330
graduate from high school
and 83% go on to college.

00:05:03.330 --> 00:05:07.600
We will hear the welcome from
the president's of the Chief

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:10.200
Marshal of the
Harvard Association.

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:11.990
They're just coming
down the aisle.

00:05:11.990 --> 00:05:12.925
You see can see that--

00:05:12.925 --> 00:05:16.650
They're the class of 1928
to the class of 1958.

00:05:16.650 --> 00:05:20.400
Our oldest alumni today
are in that group.

00:05:20.400 --> 00:05:23.920
You'll see the men
in their top hats.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:26.550
Those are men who belong
to the Happy Observance

00:05:26.550 --> 00:05:29.620
of Commencement Committee,
Alumni Association committee

00:05:29.620 --> 00:05:34.640
that was founded in the
1860s to make sure everybody

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:37.350
would be happy on
commencement day.

00:05:37.350 --> 00:05:39.300
Although, Rennie, I
understand they also

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:41.510
began to serve alcohol
on commencement,

00:05:41.510 --> 00:05:44.190
and that made the
people even happier.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:46.350
You see the men have
their black top hats.

00:05:46.350 --> 00:05:50.510
The women-- you saw earlier
my hat with the feathers.

00:05:50.510 --> 00:05:52.500
That's the woman's
version of the top hat,

00:05:52.500 --> 00:05:54.920
and we see many women
in Harvard Yard today

00:05:54.920 --> 00:05:56.420
who have the top hats.

00:05:56.420 --> 00:06:00.670
So here we have the procession
of our oldest alumni.

00:06:00.670 --> 00:06:05.530
And today we're happy to welcome
the two oldest alumni, Lillian

00:06:05.530 --> 00:06:09.690
Sugarman from the
Radcliffe class of 1937

00:06:09.690 --> 00:06:15.686
and Robert Rothschild from
the Harvard class of 1939.

00:06:15.686 --> 00:06:21.280
Our President of the Harvard
Alumni Association this year

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:26.470
is Catherine A. Gellert,
AB '93, known as Kate.

00:06:26.470 --> 00:06:30.860
Kate joined the HAA as an
elected director in 2007.

00:06:30.860 --> 00:06:33.350
She is a former co-chair
of the Executive Committee

00:06:33.350 --> 00:06:36.100
of the Harvard College
Fund and Vice President

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:39.000
of Harvard's Engagement
and Marketing Committee.

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.690
A Class Reunion
Gift Chair, she also

00:06:41.690 --> 00:06:44.660
served as treasurer of the
Harvard Club of New York City

00:06:44.660 --> 00:06:47.570
before becoming
the HAA president.

00:06:47.570 --> 00:06:49.520
Kate has an MBA from Columbia.

00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:52.580
She works in her family's
Manhattan private investment

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:55.410
business, the
Windcrest Partners.

00:06:55.410 --> 00:07:00.370
Her parents, Michael E. Gellert,
class of '53, and Mary C.

00:07:00.370 --> 00:07:03.980
Gellert, a 1957 graduate of
the Harvard Radcliffe Program

00:07:03.980 --> 00:07:07.340
in Business Administration.

00:07:07.340 --> 00:07:10.770
And we see now the
25th Reunion Class.

00:07:10.770 --> 00:07:14.990
The great class of 1989
is filing onto the stage.

00:07:14.990 --> 00:07:17.380
They're passing
right in front of us.

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:22.120
And there are
hundreds of members

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:26.900
of the class we will have return
today for their 25th reunion.

00:07:26.900 --> 00:07:29.350
The 25th reunion
is considered to be

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:32.960
the major reunion
of a Harvard class.

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:36.380
And it's the 25th, the
30th, and the 50th classes

00:07:36.380 --> 00:07:39.554
who are celebrating
with us today.

00:07:39.554 --> 00:07:43.700
The 30th, 35th, and
40th may be here,

00:07:43.700 --> 00:07:47.190
but the chances are that they
are not because they will hold

00:07:47.190 --> 00:07:49.950
their reunions in
the fall, next fall.

00:07:49.950 --> 00:07:54.240
And this helps with the
Alumni Association staff

00:07:54.240 --> 00:07:58.230
because it doesn't
give them as much work

00:07:58.230 --> 00:08:01.790
to do when they would
have all of the classes.

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:07.850
So we're seating the classes
proceeding now down the aisle.

00:08:07.850 --> 00:08:13.690
When Kate comes up, she will
welcome us all here today.

00:08:13.690 --> 00:08:17.325
And then we will sing
"Gaudeamus Igitur,"

00:08:17.325 --> 00:08:22.000
or "So Let Us Rejoice," which is
a popular former academic hymn

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:23.850
sung in Latin.

00:08:23.850 --> 00:08:27.490
Despite its use as such, it
is a jocular, light-hearted

00:08:27.490 --> 00:08:30.560
composition that pokes
fun at university life.

00:08:30.560 --> 00:08:33.850
The song dates to the
early 18th century

00:08:33.850 --> 00:08:37.990
based on the Latin
manuscript from 1287.

00:08:37.990 --> 00:08:39.560
It was known as a
beer-drinking song

00:08:39.560 --> 00:08:41.929
in many ancient
universities, and it

00:08:41.929 --> 00:08:44.390
tells you to live the
fullest even though you

00:08:44.390 --> 00:08:46.550
know you can die sometime.

00:08:46.550 --> 00:08:49.120
This is including
singing this song.

00:08:49.120 --> 00:08:52.030
We will sing it cheerfully.

00:08:52.030 --> 00:08:55.750
It's a beautiful day here in
Cambridge, a perfect afternoon.

00:08:55.750 --> 00:08:59.750
It's sunny and cool with
the temperature in the 60s.

00:08:59.750 --> 00:09:01.360
Those of us on the
Happy Committee

00:09:01.360 --> 00:09:05.170
firmly believe that our
late beloved university

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:09.340
minister Peter Gomes is
managing things from on high

00:09:09.340 --> 00:09:11.230
to make sure we had
a beautiful day.

00:09:11.230 --> 00:09:12.790
Yesterday it was cold and rainy.

00:09:12.790 --> 00:09:15.390
Tomorrow it is predicted
to be cold and rainy.

00:09:15.390 --> 00:09:19.190
But our Reverend Peter Gomes
is watching out for us today,

00:09:19.190 --> 00:09:22.200
and we have a perfect
day here in Cambridge.

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:25.250
Professor Gomes, who was the
Plummer Professor of Christian

00:09:25.250 --> 00:09:27.880
Morals for more
than 40 years, has

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:31.730
said of Harvard commencement
that, "Someone observing

00:09:31.730 --> 00:09:35.080
the rather casual
dignity of the day

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:36.610
remarked that
commencement is more

00:09:36.610 --> 00:09:39.930
like a lawn party than a ballet.

00:09:39.930 --> 00:09:42.920
And a less charitable
but more astute observer

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:45.880
suggested that the vast
assemblage in formation

00:09:45.880 --> 00:09:49.870
in the old yard was very much
like that wonderfully chaotic

00:09:49.870 --> 00:09:52.640
game of croquet with
flamingos and hedgehogs

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:54.740
in Alice in Wonderland.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:58.120
First-time visitors are
horrified at what appears to be

00:09:58.120 --> 00:10:01.840
rank confusion"-- as you see
today what appears to be rank

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:05.740
confusion-- "but then remember
that this is after all Harvard,

00:10:05.740 --> 00:10:09.470
where conformity even of
self-preservation has been

00:10:09.470 --> 00:10:13.740
elevated to the rank
of an original sin.

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:16.020
That it works at all is
a tribute to patience

00:10:16.020 --> 00:10:19.820
and goodwill, and the general
sense that, come what may,

00:10:19.820 --> 00:10:22.870
this day is to be enjoyed."

00:10:22.870 --> 00:10:25.330
Rennie, I'm not sure we're
going to see anybody playing

00:10:25.330 --> 00:10:28.160
croquet with flamingos
today, but it is certainly

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:31.710
a beautiful sight to be sitting
here watching the alumni

00:10:31.710 --> 00:10:35.930
precess into the
Tercentenary Theatre.

00:10:35.930 --> 00:10:39.230
Well, it is a lovely
day, as Nancy said.

00:10:39.230 --> 00:10:44.224
And we can just begin to
see groups coming in now.

00:10:44.224 --> 00:10:46.650
Over the years that
I've been doing this--

00:10:46.650 --> 00:10:52.130
and I think is my 30th year
in the Happy Committee--

00:10:52.130 --> 00:10:54.330
I've watched the
tree spread grow,

00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:59.470
which is all of those graduates
over the 50th reunion class.

00:10:59.470 --> 00:11:02.980
And now that the tree
spread has grown,

00:11:02.980 --> 00:11:05.560
it takes much longer
for them to come in.

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:09.623
So notice in the picture
that you're seeing there

00:11:09.623 --> 00:11:13.670
that the oldest grads
are just beginning

00:11:13.670 --> 00:11:16.190
to make their way
into the stadium.

00:11:16.190 --> 00:11:17.710
At the same time,
we have a number

00:11:17.710 --> 00:11:20.850
of groups of younger classes,
different divisions, that

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:23.190
are coming in from
the side, on what

00:11:23.190 --> 00:11:25.890
would be stage right for you.

00:11:25.890 --> 00:11:28.780
Or if you're looking
over by University Hall,

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:32.400
they would be coming
in from there.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.460
Rennie, can we
continue with the order

00:11:35.460 --> 00:11:37.000
of the program for
this afternoon?

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.080
Absolutely.

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:42.290
Kate will start with
remarks and recognition.

00:11:42.290 --> 00:11:45.570
And my guess is she
will first recognize

00:11:45.570 --> 00:11:49.890
Richard Barth, as Nancy has
mentioned, class of '89 who's

00:11:49.890 --> 00:11:52.710
the Chief Marshal
for commencement.

00:11:52.710 --> 00:11:55.380
Traditionally,
the Chief Marshal,

00:11:55.380 --> 00:11:57.530
which we mentioned was
picked by his classmates,

00:11:57.530 --> 00:12:02.510
or her classmates
and their classmates,

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:05.070
doesn't say anything
at this ceremony,

00:12:05.070 --> 00:12:08.155
because at the end of
three days of reunioning

00:12:08.155 --> 00:12:12.380
of their 25th reunion,
chances are he

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:14.020
or she may not
have a voice left.

00:12:14.020 --> 00:12:18.760
At least that was the case
my year as the Chief Marshal.

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:23.420
I can remember asking our class
football captain Tim Anderson

00:12:23.420 --> 00:12:28.140
to sit next to me and jab
me when I closed my eyes.

00:12:28.140 --> 00:12:33.980
Needless to say, I had a very
sore arm for days afterwards.

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:38.152
I think Kate will also introduce
Robert Rothschild, which

00:12:38.152 --> 00:12:41.950
we mentioned is the oldest
grad, not the oldest living grad

00:12:41.950 --> 00:12:45.740
but the oldest grad that's here
today, and Lillian Sugarman,

00:12:45.740 --> 00:12:50.860
class of '37, who I gather
is older than he is,

00:12:50.860 --> 00:12:54.256
representing the oldest
Radcliffe graduate that's here

00:12:54.256 --> 00:12:56.248
today.

00:12:56.248 --> 00:13:02.790
At that time, we will hear from
Kate Gellert, the Announcement

00:13:02.790 --> 00:13:07.680
of Overseers, HA, directors,
and election results.

00:13:07.680 --> 00:13:10.770
And we'll wait for Kate
to make that announcement.

00:13:10.770 --> 00:13:13.860
The final tally
has just come in.

00:13:13.860 --> 00:13:20.450
It's an area that we wish more
graduates would take the time

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:21.750
to elect.

00:13:21.750 --> 00:13:24.600
It's always a small
percentage that

00:13:24.600 --> 00:13:27.142
really do elect the
overseers and the directors

00:13:27.142 --> 00:13:29.920
of the Harvard Alumni
Association, which

00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:33.320
is rather sad because it is
an opportunity for getting

00:13:33.320 --> 00:13:36.945
the best and brightest to
help serve on the overseers

00:13:36.945 --> 00:13:41.960
and for the Harvard Alumni
Association as directors.

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:48.825
After that has happened,
we'll have the presentation

00:13:48.825 --> 00:13:51.400
of the Harvard Medals.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:54.000
The Harvard Medal is
awarded by the HAA

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:57.870
for extraordinary service
to Harvard University.

00:13:57.870 --> 00:14:02.190
The word service includes
teaching, administration,

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:05.480
fundraising, and other
alumni activities.

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:07.700
Three to five
Harvard Medals have

00:14:07.700 --> 00:14:09.630
been awarded at
each commencement

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:15.370
since 1981, except for the
350th celebration in 1986

00:14:15.370 --> 00:14:18.265
when 20 medals were presented.

00:14:18.265 --> 00:14:21.770
It's an interesting
mix of graduates

00:14:21.770 --> 00:14:25.050
who have received this medal.

00:14:25.050 --> 00:14:28.710
To name but a few, Al
Gordon, class and '23,

00:14:28.710 --> 00:14:31.310
who Gordon Track
Center is named after

00:14:31.310 --> 00:14:35.220
and a very loyal alum
to Harvard in many ways.

00:14:35.220 --> 00:14:38.270
Former Radcliffe
President Matina Horner.

00:14:38.270 --> 00:14:39.840
Poet and fundraiser
David McCord,

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:48.000
whom I quoted earlier as robe
after robe scattered a rainbow.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.230
David was a much-beloved
fundraiser for Harvard,

00:14:51.230 --> 00:14:51.900
and [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:57.830
In fact, I started my career
as a father-son combination,

00:14:57.830 --> 00:15:01.985
my father class of 1919, and
I a father-son combination

00:15:01.985 --> 00:15:04.700
fundraising for David.

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:08.595
More familiar names might be
hockey coach Bill Cleary, who

00:15:08.595 --> 00:15:12.960
we've seen here today, my
old track coach Bill McCurdy,

00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:15.830
crew coach Harry Parker,
who received it last year,

00:15:15.830 --> 00:15:17.750
I believe, Nancy, if
I remember correctly.

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:18.250
Yes.

00:15:18.250 --> 00:15:20.990
Librarian Agnes Mongan.

00:15:20.990 --> 00:15:26.620
And also showing you what
extraordinary service means,

00:15:26.620 --> 00:15:30.490
Eddie Chamberlain, who for
years was Kirkland House's best

00:15:30.490 --> 00:15:32.330
beloved superintendent.

00:15:32.330 --> 00:15:35.090
And here, Rennie, we have a
picture of the 50th reunion

00:15:35.090 --> 00:15:40.390
class, the great class of 1964,
as they line up to precess

00:15:40.390 --> 00:15:42.620
into Tercentenary Theatre.

00:15:42.620 --> 00:15:47.390
Tercentenary Theatre is
called Tercentenary Theatre,

00:15:47.390 --> 00:15:51.590
and it was dedicated at the
300th anniversary celebration

00:15:51.590 --> 00:15:54.420
of Harvard's founding in 1936.

00:15:54.420 --> 00:15:58.590
It's bordered by Widener
Library, University Hall,

00:15:58.590 --> 00:16:01.760
Memorial Church, and
the great Sever Hall,

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:05.170
which was designed by the
renowned American architect

00:16:05.170 --> 00:16:09.160
and Harvard graduate
H.H. Richardson.

00:16:09.160 --> 00:16:12.840
The tent which the
dignitaries are under

00:16:12.840 --> 00:16:17.620
was replaced from an old one
that leaked badly in 1985.

00:16:17.620 --> 00:16:21.010
So the present tent
when it is replaced

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:23.590
will become part
of the past tense.

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:32.580
Maybe I ought to get a
symbol crash on that, Nancy.

00:16:32.580 --> 00:16:38.130
We'll progress down
after the presentation

00:16:38.130 --> 00:16:43.654
of the medals, which if not,
we can mention those, perhaps.

00:16:43.654 --> 00:16:44.820
You've got them right there.

00:16:44.820 --> 00:16:46.850
I've got them here, I think.

00:16:46.850 --> 00:16:49.820
Unfortunately,
there are usually,

00:16:49.820 --> 00:16:53.250
as I said, any number of
them, but they're usually

00:16:53.250 --> 00:16:55.340
have been three in the past.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:17:03.640
And this year there will be only
two presented at this ceremony.

00:17:03.640 --> 00:17:07.319
It will be Louis Newell
from the class of 1957.

00:17:07.319 --> 00:17:10.740
Unfortunately, he is
unable to be with us today.

00:17:10.740 --> 00:17:13.430
But Emily Pulitzer.

00:17:13.430 --> 00:17:14.480
Right.

00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:16.619
And Anand Mahindra.

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:22.579
Anand is from the class
of 1977, MBA 1981.

00:17:22.579 --> 00:17:31.630
And Emily Pulitzer received a
Master of Arts degree in 1963.

00:17:31.630 --> 00:17:34.920
I should mention we will
watch the 50th reunion go by,

00:17:34.920 --> 00:17:37.060
that that's Scott
Harshbarger's class.

00:17:37.060 --> 00:17:40.980
There it is, the
great class of 1964.

00:17:40.980 --> 00:17:43.860
Interesting, the reunion
classes as they come in,

00:17:43.860 --> 00:17:47.340
Nancy mentioned the 80th
as being the oldest,

00:17:47.340 --> 00:17:51.002
but perhaps the class
of 1970 and 1944

00:17:51.002 --> 00:17:53.660
is having their 70th reunion.

00:17:53.660 --> 00:17:55.320
And that's an
interesting classes

00:17:55.320 --> 00:17:57.580
in that their
class secretary who

00:17:57.580 --> 00:18:03.010
was appointed at the time
they graduate, Dan Fenn,

00:18:03.010 --> 00:18:07.120
has been at it ever since 1944.

00:18:07.120 --> 00:18:12.200
He's the oldest class secretary
and the oldest in longevity.

00:18:12.200 --> 00:18:16.840
And it's interesting to
note that the class of 1944,

00:18:16.840 --> 00:18:20.920
as far as we know, the only
class to have had five Nobel

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:24.890
Prize winners in it-- two
presidential advisers, of which

00:18:24.890 --> 00:18:27.480
Dan Fenn was actually--
Dan Fenn headed up

00:18:27.480 --> 00:18:29.900
the Kennedy Library
at one point.

00:18:29.900 --> 00:18:35.230
And two former
musical composers.

00:18:35.230 --> 00:18:41.270
So it's a well-known class, and
there are quite a few of them

00:18:41.270 --> 00:18:42.280
here today.

00:18:42.280 --> 00:18:46.150
Continuing with the afternoon
program, Kate Gellert

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:51.270
will inform us of class gifts
to the Harvard College Fund.

00:18:51.270 --> 00:18:54.450
One gift that is the
most important gift

00:18:54.450 --> 00:18:59.090
was one by Ken Griffin,
who gave $175 million

00:18:59.090 --> 00:19:02.885
to Harvard College, which is the
biggest single gift ever made

00:19:02.885 --> 00:19:04.170
to Harvard College.

00:19:04.170 --> 00:19:09.400
The money will largely go to
the college's financial aid

00:19:09.400 --> 00:19:10.660
program.

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:13.050
The annual cost of
attending Harvard College

00:19:13.050 --> 00:19:17.910
is currently $60,000,
and more than 70%

00:19:17.910 --> 00:19:19.810
of Harvard
undergraduates receive

00:19:19.810 --> 00:19:24.560
some form of financial aid.

00:19:24.560 --> 00:19:27.520
Good deal of that, probably
$40 million of that,

00:19:27.520 --> 00:19:31.600
which Nancy mentioned, will go
towards creating 200 Griffin

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:36.260
scholars, and $125 million
providing three-to-one matching

00:19:36.260 --> 00:19:41.110
funds for a new program that's
to create 600 scholarship.

00:19:41.110 --> 00:19:44.140
In return, Harvard will rename
its college financial aid

00:19:44.140 --> 00:19:47.090
office and its director's
title after Griffin.

00:19:47.090 --> 00:19:51.026
Griffin, who is estimated
worth 4.4 billion,

00:19:51.026 --> 00:19:55.946
founded Citadel one year
after graduating from Harvard.

00:19:55.946 --> 00:19:59.650
Harvard embarked last
September on a $6.5

00:19:59.650 --> 00:20:05.800
billion-dollar campaign, and
this gift from Ken Griffin

00:20:05.800 --> 00:20:09.380
will be part of that Harvard
campaign, which I understand,

00:20:09.380 --> 00:20:10.845
Rennie, is going very well.

00:20:10.845 --> 00:20:13.580
And so Harvard's trying
to raise $6.5 million

00:20:13.580 --> 00:20:18.382
over the course of
the next five years.

00:20:18.382 --> 00:20:20.740
It's going along well,
as I understand it.

00:20:24.770 --> 00:20:29.670
We call ourselves in the Alumni
Association the friendraisers.

00:20:29.670 --> 00:20:33.980
And we call our colleagues in
the money-raising end of it

00:20:33.980 --> 00:20:35.320
the fundraisers.

00:20:35.320 --> 00:20:39.610
So both of them
work well together.

00:20:39.610 --> 00:20:44.730
After the introduction and we
hear about the financial end

00:20:44.730 --> 00:20:48.650
of things, the
band will come down

00:20:48.650 --> 00:20:51.030
the aisles playing
"Harvardiana."

00:20:51.030 --> 00:20:53.020
They'll swing down
the center aisle

00:20:53.020 --> 00:20:55.600
with a collection of
Harvard fight songs,

00:20:55.600 --> 00:20:59.816
including Tom Lehrer's
"Fight Fiercely Harvard."

00:20:59.816 --> 00:21:01.190
Some of you may
be aware of this.

00:21:01.190 --> 00:21:03.740
He put this together
back in the '50s.

00:21:03.740 --> 00:21:05.160
"Fight fiercely, Harvard.

00:21:05.160 --> 00:21:06.870
Fight, fight, fight.

00:21:06.870 --> 00:21:09.610
Demonstrate to them our will.

00:21:09.610 --> 00:21:14.242
Albeit they possess the might,
nevertheless we have the will.

00:21:14.242 --> 00:21:16.640
We will celebrate our victory.

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:19.080
We'll have the whole
team up for tea.

00:21:19.080 --> 00:21:20.496
How jolly.

00:21:20.496 --> 00:21:22.856
Throw that spheroid
down the field,

00:21:22.856 --> 00:21:26.380
and fight, fight, fight."

00:21:26.380 --> 00:21:30.600
Following Harvardiana, we will
have the report to the alumni

00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:33.860
by our president,
Drew Gilpin Faust.

00:21:33.860 --> 00:21:36.690
She is the 28th president
of the university,

00:21:36.690 --> 00:21:40.390
and she will give us her annual
report, which will give us

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:42.680
a picture of current
happenings along with a view

00:21:42.680 --> 00:21:46.170
toward the future.

00:21:46.170 --> 00:21:48.810
She will be with
us tomorrow, too,

00:21:48.810 --> 00:21:52.940
when we celebrate Radcliffe
Day and receive the Radcliffe

00:21:52.940 --> 00:21:53.440
Medal.

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:56.090
It's been 15 years
now that the Radcliffe

00:21:56.090 --> 00:21:58.390
Institute took over the Harvard.

00:21:58.390 --> 00:22:02.330
You may know that Radcliffe
was founded as the Harvard

00:22:02.330 --> 00:22:08.680
Annex in 1879 and chartered
as Radcliffe in 1894.

00:22:08.680 --> 00:22:12.010
It merged with Harvard in 1999.

00:22:12.010 --> 00:22:17.950
From 1963 to 1976, just
before Nancy graduated,

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:22.100
the Harvard diplomas were signed
by both Radcliffe and Harvard.

00:22:22.100 --> 00:22:25.500
My diploma is more valuable
than yours, Rennie,

00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:28.700
because I have two presidents
who signed my diploma

00:22:28.700 --> 00:22:30.120
and you only have one.

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:30.980
That's true.

00:22:30.980 --> 00:22:31.920
That's true.

00:22:31.920 --> 00:22:35.233
Well, I get a lot of
kidding from my wife who

00:22:35.233 --> 00:22:36.890
was a Radcliffe graduate.

00:22:36.890 --> 00:22:38.870
I always said she was
the magna cum laude

00:22:38.870 --> 00:22:41.420
and I was the laude
[? a ?] cumma.

00:22:41.420 --> 00:22:43.680
In any case we will--

00:22:43.680 --> 00:22:45.770
After the report
to the alumni, we

00:22:45.770 --> 00:22:48.900
will sing the
Radcliffe alma mater,

00:22:48.900 --> 00:22:52.070
"Radcliffe, Now We
Rise to Greet Thee."

00:22:52.070 --> 00:22:55.130
And following that, we will
have the principal commencement

00:22:55.130 --> 00:22:55.650
address.

00:22:55.650 --> 00:22:58.420
It will be given by
Michael Bloomberg,

00:22:58.420 --> 00:23:02.100
the former mayor
of New York City.

00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:04.940
Prior to that, he founded
Bloomberg Communications,

00:23:04.940 --> 00:23:10.460
which is a global
communications firm.

00:23:10.460 --> 00:23:15.870
Since leaving the mayor
office in New York City,

00:23:15.870 --> 00:23:20.650
he runs Bloomberg Philanthropies
and he's the UN special envoy

00:23:20.650 --> 00:23:23.440
for cities and climate change.

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:27.450
He's also done work
to try to increase

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:29.980
gun control in
the United States.

00:23:29.980 --> 00:23:35.240
So we're all looking forward
to Michael Bloomberg's address.

00:23:35.240 --> 00:23:37.275
He graduated from Johns
Hopkins University

00:23:37.275 --> 00:23:40.890
for his undergraduate degree,
and then he received an MBA

00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:44.300
from Harvard Business
School in 1966.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.330
And today he received
an honorary degree

00:23:47.330 --> 00:23:49.520
of Doctor of Laws.

00:23:49.520 --> 00:23:51.580
Yes, he's a local boy.

00:23:51.580 --> 00:23:56.225
He was born in 1942, and raised
here, and lived in Medford.

00:23:56.225 --> 00:23:58.885
And attended, as Nancy
said, Johns Hopkins

00:23:58.885 --> 00:24:00.520
then the Harvard
Business School.

00:24:00.520 --> 00:24:02.980
And he told us last night
when he was growing up

00:24:02.980 --> 00:24:08.290
he wasn't much of a Red Sox fan,
but he was a rabid Celtics fan.

00:24:08.290 --> 00:24:11.680
And when he went to games
in New York City or Boston,

00:24:11.680 --> 00:24:15.150
where the New York Knicks
play the Boston Celtics,

00:24:15.150 --> 00:24:18.800
he wouldn't cheer
for either team.

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:21.870
Well, we're glad to have him
here today to speak to us.

00:24:21.870 --> 00:24:23.350
It'll be quite interesting.

00:24:23.350 --> 00:24:26.192
We've had some interesting
speeches over the year.

00:24:26.192 --> 00:24:28.250
I was looking over
the list of those

00:24:28.250 --> 00:24:30.705
who have spoken
to us in the past,

00:24:30.705 --> 00:24:32.560
and if I can find
it here, I thought

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:34.570
I might mention some of
the interesting things

00:24:34.570 --> 00:24:35.653
that they've talked about.

00:24:41.210 --> 00:24:43.440
While Rennie's
looking for his list,

00:24:43.440 --> 00:24:46.070
we will finish the
afternoon exercises

00:24:46.070 --> 00:24:50.870
with the singing of "Fair
Harvard," the Harvard

00:24:50.870 --> 00:24:55.600
alma mater, composed by Samuel
Gilman of the class of 1811.

00:24:55.600 --> 00:24:59.060
Rennie, do you realize that he
graduated more than 200 years

00:24:59.060 --> 00:25:05.310
ago and we still sing two verses
of the song that he wrote?

00:25:05.310 --> 00:25:10.446
It's interesting to note that
the song that he composed

00:25:10.446 --> 00:25:14.970
read, "Fair Harvard thy
sons to the jubilee throne."

00:25:14.970 --> 00:25:16.970
And there was a
lot of discussion

00:25:16.970 --> 00:25:21.280
about this when Radcliffe
joined and merged with Harvard.

00:25:21.280 --> 00:25:24.360
And the feeling was that
the verse should be changed.

00:25:24.360 --> 00:25:27.890
And indeed it was changed
to "Fair Harvard, we

00:25:27.890 --> 00:25:30.310
join in thy jubilee throne."

00:25:30.310 --> 00:25:33.970
It's interesting to note that
Champ Lyons of the class of '62

00:25:33.970 --> 00:25:36.045
was one of our
former HAA presidents

00:25:36.045 --> 00:25:40.880
and a lawyer and judge in the
southern part of the country.

00:25:40.880 --> 00:25:43.730
His recommendation was
that it would be called,

00:25:43.730 --> 00:25:47.150
suggested it be, "Fair
Harvard, thy sibs,

00:25:47.150 --> 00:25:49.550
to thy jubilee throne."

00:25:49.550 --> 00:25:54.290
And that will be the end of
our commencement afternoon

00:25:54.290 --> 00:25:55.930
exercises.

00:25:55.930 --> 00:26:01.120
That will be the close of the
145th meeting of the Harvard

00:26:01.120 --> 00:26:03.690
Alumni Association.

00:26:03.690 --> 00:26:06.520
And we will reconvene
then next year

00:26:06.520 --> 00:26:13.270
on May 26, 2015 for the
145th meeting of the Alumni

00:26:13.270 --> 00:26:14.410
Association.

00:26:14.410 --> 00:26:17.310
I mentioned that Michael
Bloomberg, the former mayor

00:26:17.310 --> 00:26:20.750
of New York City, received the
Doctor of Laws this morning.

00:26:20.750 --> 00:26:24.210
There were other honorary
degree recipients today.

00:26:24.210 --> 00:26:29.410
The first honorary degree that
Harvard awarded was in 1753.

00:26:29.410 --> 00:26:34.170
That was more than 100 years
after Harvard was founded.

00:26:34.170 --> 00:26:36.750
The first honorary
degree in 1753

00:26:36.750 --> 00:26:41.210
went to Benjamin Franklin
for his work on electricity.

00:26:41.210 --> 00:26:44.410
He was the most famous
American scientist

00:26:44.410 --> 00:26:46.300
and one of the most
famous scientists

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:48.300
in the world in his day.

00:26:48.300 --> 00:26:50.520
And just think, Rennie,
now we think of him

00:26:50.520 --> 00:26:54.870
as a patriot and a politician
rather than a scientist.

00:26:54.870 --> 00:26:57.230
The other honorary degree
recipients this morning

00:26:57.230 --> 00:27:01.860
were Isabel Allende, a Doctor
of Arts for the writing

00:27:01.860 --> 00:27:05.450
that she had done,
including House of Spirits.

00:27:05.450 --> 00:27:10.360
George Herbert Walker Bush,
former president of the United

00:27:10.360 --> 00:27:14.240
States, received a
Doctor of Laws degree.

00:27:14.240 --> 00:27:17.780
Aretha Franklin, the
singer, the jazz singer,

00:27:17.780 --> 00:27:19.550
received a Doctor
of Arts degree.

00:27:19.550 --> 00:27:23.300
Patricia King, the
lawyer, ethicist,

00:27:23.300 --> 00:27:26.180
and Georgetown
University Law professor,

00:27:26.180 --> 00:27:28.490
received a Doctor of Laws.

00:27:28.490 --> 00:27:33.960
Peter Raven, who's active in
biodiversity and biology work,

00:27:33.960 --> 00:27:35.960
received a Doctor of Science.

00:27:35.960 --> 00:27:39.040
Seymour Slive, the
great art historian,

00:27:39.040 --> 00:27:40.790
received a Doctor of Arts.

00:27:40.790 --> 00:27:44.780
And finally, the
economist Joseph Stieglitz

00:27:44.780 --> 00:27:46.750
received a Doctor a Law degree.

00:27:46.750 --> 00:27:50.640
We will see some of the honorary
degree recipients on stage

00:27:50.640 --> 00:27:52.600
this afternoon, and
we will point them out

00:27:52.600 --> 00:27:54.310
as they come up the aisle.

00:27:56.830 --> 00:27:58.900
I commented on the
fact that we've

00:27:58.900 --> 00:28:02.522
had some interesting speakers
at our afternoon ceremonies.

00:28:02.522 --> 00:28:04.480
You never know quite what
you're going to hear.

00:28:04.480 --> 00:28:06.430
Some of them are
better than others.

00:28:06.430 --> 00:28:10.160
But looking back
over the years, I

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:14.080
remember John
Lithgow in 2005, who

00:28:14.080 --> 00:28:17.870
said, "Be creative, be
useful, or be practical and be

00:28:17.870 --> 00:28:18.960
generous."

00:28:18.960 --> 00:28:22.500
And he had a book
that he had written

00:28:22.500 --> 00:28:25.830
at that point called Mahalia
Mouse Goes to College.

00:28:25.830 --> 00:28:28.880
And I think, as I recall
it, he read the book,

00:28:28.880 --> 00:28:30.620
and it's a children's book.

00:28:30.620 --> 00:28:32.650
And he dedicated
all the proceeds

00:28:32.650 --> 00:28:35.366
to the class of 2005
that graduated that year.

00:28:40.900 --> 00:28:46.790
J. K. Rowling spoke at the
1999 afternoon exercises,

00:28:46.790 --> 00:28:49.130
noted that the thought
of giving the address

00:28:49.130 --> 00:28:52.220
made her lose weight,
so she considered

00:28:52.220 --> 00:28:55.980
that the event was
a win-win situation.

00:28:55.980 --> 00:28:58.370
I remember she
spoke about failure,

00:28:58.370 --> 00:29:02.500
and I thought it was so brave
to get in front of the 35,000

00:29:02.500 --> 00:29:06.220
people here in Tercentenary
Theatre and talk about failure

00:29:06.220 --> 00:29:10.060
and what it is like to fail.

00:29:10.060 --> 00:29:11.720
Exactly.

00:29:11.720 --> 00:29:15.500
Last year I didn't have a chance
to note that in the morning

00:29:15.500 --> 00:29:18.260
exercises, Mike Shinagel,
who had been head

00:29:18.260 --> 00:29:21.540
of continuing ed
for years, retired.

00:29:21.540 --> 00:29:24.960
And at the time, he noted that
he was the lame duck professor

00:29:24.960 --> 00:29:29.560
who presented his graduates
for their degrees.

00:29:29.560 --> 00:29:31.410
And it reminded me of
the wonderful story

00:29:31.410 --> 00:29:35.330
that Mike tells of the fact
that when he and his wife

00:29:35.330 --> 00:29:38.980
were the house masters,
or head of the house

00:29:38.980 --> 00:29:42.700
or whatever they're called
now, of Quincy house--

00:29:42.700 --> 00:29:45.241
Quincy House apparently
has a roof garden,

00:29:45.241 --> 00:29:51.400
and Mr. and Mrs.
Mallard Duck took up

00:29:51.400 --> 00:29:53.566
residence in the garden.

00:29:53.566 --> 00:29:56.950
And Mr. Mallard Duck
left, but Mrs. Mallard

00:29:56.950 --> 00:29:59.760
stayed and laid seven eggs.

00:29:59.760 --> 00:30:02.940
And Mike's comment
was, "it shows you

00:30:02.940 --> 00:30:05.060
to what lengths a
determined mother

00:30:05.060 --> 00:30:09.150
will go to get her
children into Harvard."

00:30:09.150 --> 00:30:12.550
It's been an interesting
year here in Harvard Square.

00:30:12.550 --> 00:30:16.460
There have been a number
of personnel changes.

00:30:16.460 --> 00:30:19.170
Coming up, Rakesh
Khurana, professor

00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:22.050
of sociology and Harvard
Business School professor,

00:30:22.050 --> 00:30:27.810
will become the next dean of
Harvard College on July 1.

00:30:27.810 --> 00:30:30.790
He and his wife are also
co-masters of Cabot House.

00:30:30.790 --> 00:30:32.940
He's someone who's
dedicated to improving

00:30:32.940 --> 00:30:34.460
the lives of undergraduates.

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:39.480
And so we congratulate Professor
Khurana on his appointment

00:30:39.480 --> 00:30:41.135
and we look forward
to his service

00:30:41.135 --> 00:30:44.200
as dean of Harvard College.

00:30:44.200 --> 00:30:49.080
Our own Jack Reardon, Executive
Director of the Harvard Alumni

00:30:49.080 --> 00:30:54.700
Association for 20 years,
will be stepping down

00:30:54.700 --> 00:30:59.270
from that post as
of the end of June.

00:30:59.270 --> 00:31:02.830
And Jack will
continue his service

00:31:02.830 --> 00:31:04.920
to Harvard in various
ways, including

00:31:04.920 --> 00:31:07.340
his work with the
athletic department.

00:31:07.340 --> 00:31:10.390
He's the former
director of athletics.

00:31:10.390 --> 00:31:14.850
As well as continue to work
on the development side.

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:16.240
We will miss Jack.

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:19.580
He's from the great
class of 1960,

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:23.287
and he has really brought
the Alumni Association

00:31:23.287 --> 00:31:27.950
to its current status
as a global community

00:31:27.950 --> 00:31:32.220
of more than 350,000
of Harvard alumni.

00:31:32.220 --> 00:31:34.237
We just saw on the
screen a minute

00:31:34.237 --> 00:31:36.070
or two ago-- you may
have seen the gentleman

00:31:36.070 --> 00:31:39.450
having his picture taken
rubbing the toe of John Harvard.

00:31:39.450 --> 00:31:40.950
There it is.

00:31:40.950 --> 00:31:44.660
One of the activities that
has gone by, of course,

00:31:44.660 --> 00:31:46.920
is that in the old
days, when anybody

00:31:46.920 --> 00:31:49.550
went by John, the
undergraduates and graduates,

00:31:49.550 --> 00:31:52.080
everybody tipped
their hat to him.

00:31:52.080 --> 00:31:55.440
Now they rub the toe, and it's
supposed to bring good luck.

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:57.600
So if you ever come
to Harvard Yard

00:31:57.600 --> 00:31:59.320
and you look at
John Harvard's toe,

00:31:59.320 --> 00:32:03.470
you realize it is completely
polished bronze because of all

00:32:03.470 --> 00:32:05.190
the people who've
been touching it.

00:32:05.190 --> 00:32:08.570
Imagine what the statute would
look like if the entire statute

00:32:08.570 --> 00:32:10.310
where that brightly
colored bronze.

00:32:10.310 --> 00:32:12.230
And what you're
seeing there-- there

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:14.480
is my classmate Alan Howl.

00:32:14.480 --> 00:32:18.650
And there is my good wife, I
think, somewhere in the group

00:32:18.650 --> 00:32:19.150
there.

00:32:19.150 --> 00:32:20.525
It's nice to know
they're seated.

00:32:20.525 --> 00:32:22.080
The great class of 1955.

00:32:22.080 --> 00:32:23.070
1955.

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:26.400
And I was going to note that,
of course, if you come and see

00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:29.120
the John Harvard statue, you
should realize it's often

00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:32.880
called the Statue of Three Lies,
because the information on it

00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:36.240
and the picture you just
of John Harvard's head--

00:32:36.240 --> 00:32:37.730
that's not John Harvard.

00:32:37.730 --> 00:32:41.260
Nobody knows what
he looked like.

00:32:41.260 --> 00:32:46.170
Name is Sherman Hoar,
used by Donald Chester

00:32:46.170 --> 00:32:48.740
French as the model for it.

00:32:48.740 --> 00:32:53.162
And you'll also note that it
gives the date on it as 1636.

00:32:53.162 --> 00:32:56.574
And of course that's not the
date that Harvard was formed.

00:32:56.574 --> 00:32:59.350
It was formed in 1632.

00:32:59.350 --> 00:33:01.530
And I'm blanking
on the third one,

00:33:01.530 --> 00:33:07.560
but I think that it
was not in Cambridge.

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:08.498
It was Newtown.

00:33:08.498 --> 00:33:10.380
That's the third one if
I remember correctly.

00:33:10.380 --> 00:33:13.100
But anyway, there are three
lies connected with it.

00:33:13.100 --> 00:33:16.215
And we hope that everybody who's
rubbing the foot at this time

00:33:16.215 --> 00:33:18.290
is at least having
some good luck,

00:33:18.290 --> 00:33:20.410
and perhaps we
rubbed it yesterday

00:33:20.410 --> 00:33:22.410
to get the good weather, Nancy.

00:33:22.410 --> 00:33:24.740
One of the things I love
about Harvard commencement

00:33:24.740 --> 00:33:28.200
is we are in the actual
place where commencement

00:33:28.200 --> 00:33:31.480
have been celebrated since 1642.

00:33:31.480 --> 00:33:35.290
In the early years of college,
the elders of the Massachusetts

00:33:35.290 --> 00:33:37.280
Bay Colony who
founded the college

00:33:37.280 --> 00:33:40.310
to train ministers
for the colony,

00:33:40.310 --> 00:33:42.680
they were concerned that the
college wouldn't survive.

00:33:42.680 --> 00:33:46.390
And so they would come
en masse from Boston

00:33:46.390 --> 00:33:50.970
to celebrate, listen to the
orations of the graduates,

00:33:50.970 --> 00:33:52.170
and celebrate.

00:33:52.170 --> 00:33:55.421
And the next year they invited
the alumni and the following

00:33:55.421 --> 00:33:55.920
year.

00:33:55.920 --> 00:34:00.600
So our alumni tradition
dates actually from 1643,

00:34:00.600 --> 00:34:03.650
and it has always happened
right here on this site.

00:34:03.650 --> 00:34:07.550
There are several
traditions that date

00:34:07.550 --> 00:34:12.570
from the 17th and 18th
century, including that beer

00:34:12.570 --> 00:34:16.510
is served free in the old
yard on commencement day.

00:34:16.510 --> 00:34:19.000
So this morning as I was
walking through the yard,

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:22.420
I saw the trucks being
unloaded with kegs of beer.

00:34:22.420 --> 00:34:26.389
So if you're ever in the Boston
area on commencement day,

00:34:26.389 --> 00:34:28.580
you can come during
lunch and you

00:34:28.580 --> 00:34:31.219
will be offered a glass of beer.

00:34:31.219 --> 00:34:32.489
There's another tradition.

00:34:32.489 --> 00:34:35.460
Rennie, you and I both
live here in Cambridge.

00:34:35.460 --> 00:34:37.900
And it is in fact in
the charter of Harvard

00:34:37.900 --> 00:34:42.760
that Cambridge residents
can graze their sheep

00:34:42.760 --> 00:34:44.010
in Harvard Yard.

00:34:44.010 --> 00:34:47.300
So one year I would
like to bring my sheep,

00:34:47.300 --> 00:34:50.260
if I ever have any, into
Harvard Yard so they can graze

00:34:50.260 --> 00:34:54.060
and enjoy the commencement
festivities, as well.

00:34:54.060 --> 00:34:57.730
In the 18th century,
there would sometimes

00:34:57.730 --> 00:35:00.980
be circus animals,
including elephants,

00:35:00.980 --> 00:35:04.920
and men dressed up as mermaids.

00:35:04.920 --> 00:35:09.610
And I can just imagine
seeing elephants and mermaids

00:35:09.610 --> 00:35:11.330
on Harvard Yard.

00:35:11.330 --> 00:35:14.630
Unfortunately, we won't see
any of those characters today.

00:35:14.630 --> 00:35:15.600
Probably not.

00:35:15.600 --> 00:35:18.260
Probably not.

00:35:18.260 --> 00:35:22.125
During lunch, there was
a number of the graduates

00:35:22.125 --> 00:35:23.760
with their mortar boards on.

00:35:23.760 --> 00:35:25.850
And the discussion came
up as to whether you

00:35:25.850 --> 00:35:29.160
put your tassel on the
left and then moved it over

00:35:29.160 --> 00:35:33.143
to the right, which always comes
up at commencement whether it

00:35:33.143 --> 00:35:38.260
be at college like Harvard here
or high schools and so forth.

00:35:38.260 --> 00:35:42.070
And one year a graduate
wore a ponytail

00:35:42.070 --> 00:35:50.000
and told those around him,
remind me when I graduate

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:54.250
and I'll flip my pony
tail from left to right.

00:35:54.250 --> 00:35:59.600
A nice sentiment, but there
is no meaning attached to

00:35:59.600 --> 00:36:03.640
whether the tassel
drapes right or left.

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:06.980
Otherwise, an expert in such
matters has noted, quote,

00:36:06.980 --> 00:36:11.390
"a gust of wind could change
your academic standing

00:36:11.390 --> 00:36:13.600
in a moment."

00:36:13.600 --> 00:36:17.650
Thursday is our commencement
day here at Harvard, so not

00:36:17.650 --> 00:36:20.000
only the undergraduates
but the graduates

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:23.670
of all the professional schools
are with us in the morning

00:36:23.670 --> 00:36:27.490
and in the afternoon for
the afternoon exercises.

00:36:27.490 --> 00:36:30.090
Wednesdays of
graduation week are

00:36:30.090 --> 00:36:34.380
what we call Class Day, where
each of the individual schools

00:36:34.380 --> 00:36:36.170
invites a speaker.

00:36:36.170 --> 00:36:41.570
So yesterday, Sheryl Sandberg,
Chief Operating Officer

00:36:41.570 --> 00:36:46.340
of Facebook, and graduate
of Harvard College '91,

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:51.120
Harvard Business School '95,
addressed the senior class.

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:53.520
At the Kennedy School,
Samantha Power,

00:36:53.520 --> 00:36:59.830
who has a JD from Harvard,
a law degree from Harvard,

00:36:59.830 --> 00:37:04.100
class of 1999, who is currently
the US Ambassador to the United

00:37:04.100 --> 00:37:07.220
Nations and a former professor
at the Kennedy School--

00:37:07.220 --> 00:37:10.150
she spoke to the Kennedy
School graduates.

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:13.700
The medical school
invited Vivek Murthy, who

00:37:13.700 --> 00:37:18.170
is the current nominee to be the
US Surgeon General and founder

00:37:18.170 --> 00:37:21.220
of Doctors for
America, addressed

00:37:21.220 --> 00:37:24.240
the medical and dental
school graduates.

00:37:24.240 --> 00:37:26.580
At the business
school, Salman Khan,

00:37:26.580 --> 00:37:30.650
who is the founder of the
first free online education

00:37:30.650 --> 00:37:35.660
Khan Academy addressed
the MBA graduates.

00:37:35.660 --> 00:37:38.640
At the School of Public
Health, Thomas Friedan,

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:41.930
who's the director of the
Center for Disease Control,

00:37:41.930 --> 00:37:45.040
talked to the graduates.

00:37:45.040 --> 00:37:47.500
At the Graduate
School of Design,

00:37:47.500 --> 00:37:49.780
Michael Van Valkenburgh,
the professor

00:37:49.780 --> 00:37:53.680
of landscape architecture spoke.

00:37:53.680 --> 00:37:56.900
At the law school,
Preet Bharara,

00:37:56.900 --> 00:38:01.420
who overseas investigation
and litigation

00:38:01.420 --> 00:38:04.550
of criminal and
civil cases, was one

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:07.130
of the speakers, along
with Mindy Kaling, who's

00:38:07.130 --> 00:38:12.800
a writer and producer known for
playing Kelly Kapoor on the NBC

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:15.470
sitcom "The Office."

00:38:15.470 --> 00:38:17.690
Graduate School
of Education were

00:38:17.690 --> 00:38:20.850
addressed by Michael Johnston,
who's a Colorado State

00:38:20.850 --> 00:38:23.400
senator and a graduate
of the ed school.

00:38:23.400 --> 00:38:25.905
And at the divinity
school, Charles Hallisey,

00:38:25.905 --> 00:38:31.890
who is a lecturer on Buddhist
literature, gave the address.

00:38:31.890 --> 00:38:34.800
So it's always a
busy couple of days.

00:38:34.800 --> 00:38:39.430
Wednesday is Class Day where
each school individually

00:38:39.430 --> 00:38:40.210
celebrates.

00:38:40.210 --> 00:38:44.340
And today is the day for the
university-wide celebration.

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:47.940
We're expecting probably
20,000 people today

00:38:47.940 --> 00:38:51.580
here in Harvard Yard to
hear Michael Bloomberg.

00:38:51.580 --> 00:38:55.840
The yard can seat
as many as 35,000.

00:38:55.840 --> 00:39:00.520
And I remember for the Bill
Gates and J. K. Rowling,

00:39:00.520 --> 00:39:03.440
we had 35,000,
standing room only.

00:39:03.440 --> 00:39:06.690
Not sure we'll quite reach
that, but we should easily

00:39:06.690 --> 00:39:11.220
have 20,000 people
here with us today.

00:39:11.220 --> 00:39:14.480
Well, it won't be as
crowded in the afternoon.

00:39:14.480 --> 00:39:16.240
Mornings fill up,
and we often say

00:39:16.240 --> 00:39:23.350
it's an event for the 35,000
people and 27,000 seats,

00:39:23.350 --> 00:39:25.140
which makes it
somewhat difficult.

00:39:25.140 --> 00:39:30.340
But the atmosphere is such
that the university has never

00:39:30.340 --> 00:39:34.260
made any effort to
accommodate all of the parents

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:37.660
and so forth, which is difficult
for them in the morning.

00:39:37.660 --> 00:39:42.080
But to ever consider moving
it down to the stadium

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:45.760
where Class Day exercises
in the old days were held

00:39:45.760 --> 00:39:47.225
has never been considered.

00:39:47.225 --> 00:39:49.410
I think part of it is
because we're lucky enough

00:39:49.410 --> 00:39:50.946
to have a lot of
good, nice trees

00:39:50.946 --> 00:39:53.075
that are well taken
care of up here

00:39:53.075 --> 00:39:55.250
that give us a
pretty good shade.

00:39:55.250 --> 00:39:57.920
And not too many trees,
too, so the people

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:00.290
can't see around them.

00:40:00.290 --> 00:40:04.825
Years ago, back in 2004,
because of the crowds

00:40:04.825 --> 00:40:07.090
and because it's
difficult to see around

00:40:07.090 --> 00:40:09.820
some of the trees and
things, the university put

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:13.544
in the first of its LED screens.

00:40:13.544 --> 00:40:16.029
And we had two of
them at that time.

00:40:16.029 --> 00:40:19.240
I think we now have,
one, two, at least four

00:40:19.240 --> 00:40:23.475
with an additional one put
up in the old yard where

00:40:23.475 --> 00:40:26.157
the general alumni
spread is, which

00:40:26.157 --> 00:40:28.807
helped to take care of
those who couldn't find

00:40:28.807 --> 00:40:30.735
a seat within the
stadium itself.

00:40:30.735 --> 00:40:34.490
So they have been a great help.

00:40:34.490 --> 00:40:39.970
Not only do you see them,
but because you can read

00:40:39.970 --> 00:40:41.844
what's being said if
you can't hear it,

00:40:41.844 --> 00:40:43.580
which you generally can't.

00:40:43.580 --> 00:40:45.500
You're seeing a lot
of interesting hats

00:40:45.500 --> 00:40:47.507
as we go around here.

00:40:47.507 --> 00:40:51.160
And Nancy, I'm sure, could
tell you more about that hats,

00:40:51.160 --> 00:40:54.860
but I can remember having
served on the first committee

00:40:54.860 --> 00:40:56.500
about women's wear.

00:40:56.500 --> 00:41:00.245
And in the old days,
women wore all white.

00:41:00.245 --> 00:41:02.050
It was dictated
they all wore white.

00:41:02.050 --> 00:41:05.510
Now, as I understand
it, that's not something

00:41:05.510 --> 00:41:09.440
that every good-looking
woman has in their wardrobe.

00:41:09.440 --> 00:41:12.320
So we had quite a
committee put together,

00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:14.672
because it was white
with a red sash.

00:41:14.672 --> 00:41:20.230
The red sash was attached with
a carnation at the bottom,

00:41:20.230 --> 00:41:24.310
and in some cases, a
very [INAUDIBLE] hat

00:41:24.310 --> 00:41:26.970
that was just awful.

00:41:26.970 --> 00:41:30.650
And we had a meeting on this,
and there was a lot of venting.

00:41:30.650 --> 00:41:32.830
In fact, at the
meeting-- it took place,

00:41:32.830 --> 00:41:34.980
I think, at one of
the HAA meetings

00:41:34.980 --> 00:41:46.990
in the Commonwealth HAA,
the Commonwealth office

00:41:46.990 --> 00:41:50.580
of the Harvard Club of Boston.

00:41:50.580 --> 00:41:52.810
And Myra Mayman,
who at that time

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:56.850
was the head of the arts,
which Jack Megan now is,

00:41:56.850 --> 00:42:03.560
Myra got quite excited about
this and got going on it.

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:07.105
And the alarm went off.

00:42:07.105 --> 00:42:11.432
The fire alarm went off, and
we had to vacate the building.

00:42:11.432 --> 00:42:16.030
But we then changed the ruling
to that you could either

00:42:16.030 --> 00:42:19.920
wear black or white, but
you couldn't wear both

00:42:19.920 --> 00:42:23.240
because then you'd look like
the Harvard dining services.

00:42:23.240 --> 00:42:27.170
Rennie, now we see the
stage is filling up

00:42:27.170 --> 00:42:31.850
with the 25th reunion class,
as well as the honorary degree

00:42:31.850 --> 00:42:35.870
recipients and the
dignitaries, our speakers

00:42:35.870 --> 00:42:37.090
for this afternoon.

00:42:37.090 --> 00:42:41.630
So I think in a few minutes,
we will be starting.

00:42:41.630 --> 00:42:43.960
You see the banners
in the trees.

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:48.530
Each of the banners represents
one school of Harvard

00:42:48.530 --> 00:42:51.650
and also the Harvard
undergraduate houses.

00:42:51.650 --> 00:42:54.160
Undergraduates at Harvard
don't live in dormitories.

00:42:54.160 --> 00:42:56.080
They live in what are
called the houses,

00:42:56.080 --> 00:42:58.450
and each house has its symbol.

00:42:58.450 --> 00:43:01.960
Each house has
its co-masters who

00:43:01.960 --> 00:43:04.840
really organize the
administrative lives

00:43:04.840 --> 00:43:05.930
of the students.

00:43:05.930 --> 00:43:09.750
Sophomores, juniors, and
seniors live in the houses,

00:43:09.750 --> 00:43:13.180
and freshman all
live in Harvard Yard.

00:43:13.180 --> 00:43:16.360
So there you can see
a view of the crowd

00:43:16.360 --> 00:43:20.700
that we are seeing from here,
some of the estimated 20,000

00:43:20.700 --> 00:43:23.370
people who will be here today.

00:43:23.370 --> 00:43:26.320
And now I believe we're
looking at the stage, which

00:43:26.320 --> 00:43:29.375
is-- yes, there on the right,
you see Alan Garber, class

00:43:29.375 --> 00:43:32.630
of 1977, who is our provost.

00:43:32.630 --> 00:43:37.510
He is sitting, waiting for
the ceremonies to begin.

00:43:37.510 --> 00:43:39.460
The woman on the left
in the white jacket

00:43:39.460 --> 00:43:42.140
is Katie Lapp, the
executive vice president

00:43:42.140 --> 00:43:44.160
of the university
who is in charge

00:43:44.160 --> 00:43:47.930
of all of the administrative
aspects of the university.

00:43:47.930 --> 00:43:56.520
And you'll see other of the
dignitaries there on the stage.

00:43:56.520 --> 00:44:00.030
Many people are still standing,
waiting for the procession

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:00.770
to conclude.

00:44:00.770 --> 00:44:05.230
Here comes the president's
procession up the center aisle.

00:44:05.230 --> 00:44:11.760
So as the president's
procession comes to the stage,

00:44:11.760 --> 00:44:17.450
we will begin our
afternoon program.

00:44:17.450 --> 00:44:20.490
What we see in the lead
there is the Chief Marshal

00:44:20.490 --> 00:44:22.970
and his aides.

00:44:22.970 --> 00:44:26.545
That's A-I-D-E-S. In the
morning, they are A-I-D-S,

00:44:26.545 --> 00:44:27.920
and we have to
get that straight.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:31.480
The Chief Marshal is the
one with the red-- looks

00:44:31.480 --> 00:44:35.430
like a red ribbon or a red
corsage, on the left side.

00:44:35.430 --> 00:44:39.170
And there is the bell signaling
the beginning of the afternoon

00:44:39.170 --> 00:44:39.760
program.

00:44:39.760 --> 00:44:42.292
So as soon as the
president and fellows--

00:44:42.292 --> 00:44:44.625
you'll see the sign there for
the president and fellows.

00:44:44.625 --> 00:44:45.170
You see--

00:44:45.170 --> 00:44:46.503
There's the president coming in.

00:44:46.503 --> 00:44:49.300
--President Drew Faust on the
right with her white jacket

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:50.730
with dark trim.

00:44:50.730 --> 00:44:52.975
And on the left,
in the middle you

00:44:52.975 --> 00:44:56.880
see Jack Reardon, the Executive
Director of the Alumni

00:44:56.880 --> 00:45:01.240
Association, class of
1960, who's stepping down.

00:45:01.240 --> 00:45:03.530
And to the left of the
screen is Kate Gellert,

00:45:03.530 --> 00:45:08.330
who's the current president of
the Harvard Alumni Association.

00:45:08.330 --> 00:45:11.860
Behind them are the directors
of the Alumni Association,

00:45:11.860 --> 00:45:14.920
former directors, current
directors, and members

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:17.106
of various committees
that have served

00:45:17.106 --> 00:45:20.440
in the Alumni Association.

00:45:20.440 --> 00:45:24.540
And you can hear the bell
from Memorial Church signaling

00:45:24.540 --> 00:45:26.550
the beginning of the
afternoon program.

00:45:26.550 --> 00:45:30.630
That's a signal for people
to take their seats.

00:45:30.630 --> 00:45:37.950
And we will continue to talk
until Kate Gellert opens

00:45:37.950 --> 00:45:41.521
the meeting with the
pounding of her gavel.

00:45:50.750 --> 00:45:53.595
We hear from time to
time the music coming up

00:45:53.595 --> 00:45:55.870
from University Hall.

00:45:55.870 --> 00:45:59.110
The stage next to the east
side of the University Hall

00:45:59.110 --> 00:46:02.320
was built for the band in 2001.

00:46:02.320 --> 00:46:06.670
There we see the Dean of
Faculty of Arts and Science,

00:46:06.670 --> 00:46:09.050
Michael Smith.

00:46:09.050 --> 00:46:11.680
And there we see the
medalists that we mentioned,

00:46:11.680 --> 00:46:14.780
Anand Mahindra, Emily Pulitzer.

00:46:14.780 --> 00:46:17.430
And normally Louis Newell
would be there as well,

00:46:17.430 --> 00:46:20.856
but unfortunately he wasn't
able to do be there today.

00:46:20.856 --> 00:46:24.470
For a long time, it was
difficult to figure out

00:46:24.470 --> 00:46:27.640
who was who, especially if
they didn't have a name tag.

00:46:27.640 --> 00:46:31.940
Now, with the signs,
it's very helpful

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:34.475
because we can line
people up behind the signs

00:46:34.475 --> 00:46:37.470
and make sure that
everybody's there.

00:46:37.470 --> 00:46:41.360
Not everybody wants
to be in parading.

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:43.810
As I said, we don't see too
many of the undergraduates who

00:46:43.810 --> 00:46:46.060
have been down at their
houses getting their diplomas.

00:46:46.060 --> 00:46:48.855
There's President Faust
with, to her left,

00:46:48.855 --> 00:46:53.380
Jim Rothenberg, the current
treasurer of the university.

00:46:53.380 --> 00:46:58.760
He will be stepping down from
that post as of July 1 to be

00:46:58.760 --> 00:47:03.570
replaced by Paul Finnegan,
who's the class of '75, MBA '82.

00:47:06.880 --> 00:47:10.055
Paul is the former president of
the Harvard Alumni Association.

00:47:22.710 --> 00:47:24.810
There is a good
view of the crowd.

00:47:24.810 --> 00:47:29.010
So I would say we're
about half full.

00:47:29.010 --> 00:47:32.600
What happens is the
graduates have all

00:47:32.600 --> 00:47:35.070
gone somewhere back to
their schools for lunch,

00:47:35.070 --> 00:47:38.170
and as the afternoon wears
on, more and more of them

00:47:38.170 --> 00:47:42.180
will be coming to hear
Michael Bloomberg speak.

00:47:42.180 --> 00:47:45.910
So we will see the chairs fill
up as the afternoon progresses.

00:47:45.910 --> 00:47:48.712
There's a good
view of the stage.

00:47:48.712 --> 00:47:51.580
The podium is to the
right of your screen,

00:47:51.580 --> 00:47:53.550
where you see the flowers.

00:47:53.550 --> 00:47:57.625
And you see the dignitaries,
the overseers, the president

00:47:57.625 --> 00:48:01.120
and fellows, the honorary
degree recipients

00:48:01.120 --> 00:48:03.630
on the stage starting
to take their seats

00:48:03.630 --> 00:48:05.435
so we can begin our program.

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:12.480
Most of the older classes
have now been seated.

00:48:12.480 --> 00:48:14.930
Class of '54 is having
their 60th reunion.

00:48:14.930 --> 00:48:18.700
That's Ted Kennedy's
class, John Calder's class,

00:48:18.700 --> 00:48:19.690
and John Updike.

00:48:19.690 --> 00:48:23.850
And I should note that John
Updike-- Houghton Library has

00:48:23.850 --> 00:48:28.420
a display of Updike's
special exhibit,

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:32.520
from 1950 to 1954
of his writings,

00:48:32.520 --> 00:48:37.340
which he gave to the
Houghton Library.

00:48:37.340 --> 00:48:39.960
There is Kate Gellert,
our president,

00:48:39.960 --> 00:48:43.610
the woman in the white dress
who has just taken her seat.

00:48:43.610 --> 00:48:46.140
She's getting ready
for the afternoon.

00:48:51.930 --> 00:48:56.250
We have quite a crew whose job
both morning and afternoon--

00:48:56.250 --> 00:49:00.880
in the morning, the seats are
all done by the university.

00:49:00.880 --> 00:49:03.690
In the afternoon, we have a
crew from the Happy Committee

00:49:03.690 --> 00:49:09.510
that helps to set up the
seating for those on the podium.

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:13.580
The older classes sit on the
far left, as we have, as I said,

00:49:13.580 --> 00:49:18.700
the bigger tent now than
in the old days and one

00:49:18.700 --> 00:49:19.850
that doesn't leak.

00:49:19.850 --> 00:49:24.060
Fortunately, we don't have
to worry about the [? rain ?]

00:49:24.060 --> 00:49:26.980
plants, so we don't
even mention it.

00:49:26.980 --> 00:49:29.970
And there we have a good view
of the podium with the flowers.

00:49:29.970 --> 00:49:34.521
That's where the speakers
will be addressing the crowd.

00:49:34.521 --> 00:49:38.130
And you can see the cage
where the different cameras

00:49:38.130 --> 00:49:38.630
are located.

00:49:41.870 --> 00:49:44.660
There's a good view of the
flowers in front of the podium.

00:49:51.859 --> 00:49:54.150
So, Rennie, we're getting a
little bit of a late start.

00:49:54.150 --> 00:49:58.990
We like to start by about
2:30, so right now we're

00:49:58.990 --> 00:50:02.410
about seven minutes
behind schedule.

00:50:02.410 --> 00:50:08.470
Normally, commencement ends at
somewhere between 4:00 and 4:15

00:50:08.470 --> 00:50:08.970
PM.

00:50:08.970 --> 00:50:14.465
We'll see if we can keep
to that schedule today.

00:50:14.465 --> 00:50:15.340
Good afternoon.

00:50:18.820 --> 00:50:19.856
Good afternoon.

00:50:23.310 --> 00:50:31.190
Honored guests, fellow alumni,
family and friends, my mom

00:50:31.190 --> 00:50:37.410
and dad, it's wonderful
to see you all here.

00:50:37.410 --> 00:50:43.627
Welcome to the 145th annual
meeting of the Harvard Alumni

00:50:43.627 --> 00:50:44.126
Association.

00:50:52.160 --> 00:50:59.246
I am Kate Gellert, member of
the college class of 1993.

00:50:59.246 --> 00:51:05.500
As the 135th president of the
Harvard Alumni Association,

00:51:05.500 --> 00:51:09.170
the HAA for short,
and in accordance

00:51:09.170 --> 00:51:14.970
with the tradition set by our
very first HAA president, John

00:51:14.970 --> 00:51:21.665
Quincy Adams, I raise this gavel
and call this meeting to order.

00:51:32.260 --> 00:51:35.990
This morning after
receiving their degrees

00:51:35.990 --> 00:51:39.080
from the college and
the graduate schools,

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:45.490
6,500 new alumni
joined our ranks.

00:51:45.490 --> 00:51:49.570
All graduates automatically
become lifelong members

00:51:49.570 --> 00:51:54.510
of the HAA, with the many
privileges and resources

00:51:54.510 --> 00:51:59.250
we hope to help you discover
in the coming years.

00:51:59.250 --> 00:52:04.040
Congratulations, and welcome
to an astounding community

00:52:04.040 --> 00:52:07.665
made only richer by
your presence among us.

00:52:15.400 --> 00:52:20.600
I also want to congratulate
your parents, your families,

00:52:20.600 --> 00:52:25.700
and friends, faculty, and
staff across the university,

00:52:25.700 --> 00:52:28.320
the people who have
believed in you

00:52:28.320 --> 00:52:33.180
and supported you throughout
your time at Harvard,

00:52:33.180 --> 00:52:37.120
and those that are
not with us here today

00:52:37.120 --> 00:52:39.990
but who would be
very proud and who

00:52:39.990 --> 00:52:44.610
are very much here
with us in spirit.

00:52:44.610 --> 00:52:46.780
When the Harvard
Alumni Association

00:52:46.780 --> 00:52:52.880
was founded in 1840, there
were no more than 10,000 living

00:52:52.880 --> 00:52:54.590
alumni.

00:52:54.590 --> 00:53:01.610
Today, you have joined over
320,000 Harvard alumni,

00:53:01.610 --> 00:53:06.320
including 17% living
outside of the United States

00:53:06.320 --> 00:53:10.250
in 189 countries.

00:53:10.250 --> 00:53:15.130
We want to welcome you,
and we want to celebrate.

00:53:15.130 --> 00:53:19.400
So please turn in your
program and join me

00:53:19.400 --> 00:53:24.660
in singing "Gaudeamus
Igitur," or in English,

00:53:24.660 --> 00:53:29.313
"So Let Us Rejoice."

00:55:06.140 --> 00:55:09.275
Why did we just sing
that song in Latin?

00:55:11.830 --> 00:55:16.030
Why am I wearing a hat?

00:55:16.030 --> 00:55:19.530
And just what does
the Happy Committee

00:55:19.530 --> 00:55:24.390
for the Observance
of Commencement do?

00:55:24.390 --> 00:55:28.640
Today is a celebration of
Harvard's most enduring

00:55:28.640 --> 00:55:30.530
traditions.

00:55:30.530 --> 00:55:33.560
We will end this
afternoon singing

00:55:33.560 --> 00:55:37.270
our alma mater, "Fair Harvard."

00:55:37.270 --> 00:55:40.280
In the second line
of the song, it

00:55:40.280 --> 00:55:44.740
will talk about the pageantry
that has unfolded today,

00:55:44.740 --> 00:55:49.510
referring to these
festival rights.

00:55:49.510 --> 00:55:52.690
Some of you in the
audience are participating

00:55:52.690 --> 00:55:56.310
in these festive rights
for the first time.

00:55:56.310 --> 00:55:59.810
Some people are here
today for the first time

00:55:59.810 --> 00:56:01.890
since they graduated.

00:56:01.890 --> 00:56:06.740
And some come back every year.

00:56:06.740 --> 00:56:08.280
I was curious.

00:56:08.280 --> 00:56:12.310
What did commencement
look like 50 years ago?

00:56:12.310 --> 00:56:15.320
Are we still flying
the same banners,

00:56:15.320 --> 00:56:18.450
singing the same songs?

00:56:18.450 --> 00:56:21.800
I did some research
about this and went

00:56:21.800 --> 00:56:27.250
where all good researchers go,
to the archives of The Crimson,

00:56:27.250 --> 00:56:33.050
where I found an article dated
Commencement Day, June 11,

00:56:33.050 --> 00:56:34.640
1964.

00:56:34.640 --> 00:56:40.420
And I quote, "Aside
from Thanksgiving,

00:56:40.420 --> 00:56:43.970
the commencement pageantry
which will gradually

00:56:43.970 --> 00:56:49.660
unravel in the yard this
morning is America's oldest

00:56:49.660 --> 00:56:52.650
continuous festival.

00:56:52.650 --> 00:56:56.450
By its forthright
uniqueness, it is also

00:56:56.450 --> 00:57:03.110
one of the most enduring
signs of everlasting Harvard."

00:57:03.110 --> 00:57:08.990
Hopefully, you, like me,
are proud of our traditions.

00:57:08.990 --> 00:57:12.830
And I am honored
through the HAA to have

00:57:12.830 --> 00:57:17.810
been the custodian of
them this past year.

00:57:17.810 --> 00:57:20.360
In the spirit of
an annual meeting,

00:57:20.360 --> 00:57:26.630
I feel obliged to report on some
of the activities of the HAA.

00:57:26.630 --> 00:57:30.800
As the university launched
the Harvard Campaign,

00:57:30.800 --> 00:57:36.440
the HAA focused on how our
alumni connect, with each other

00:57:36.440 --> 00:57:39.340
and with the university.

00:57:39.340 --> 00:57:43.830
Knowing that our alumni
desire intellectual content,

00:57:43.830 --> 00:57:48.430
we launched HarvardX for
alumni, a survey course

00:57:48.430 --> 00:57:52.530
of Harvard's offerings
on the EdX platform.

00:57:52.530 --> 00:57:57.020
Wanting to connect alumni with
campus and student life today,

00:57:57.020 --> 00:58:01.670
we launched a series called
Your Harvard, in which President

00:58:01.670 --> 00:58:06.700
Faust shares her vision for
the future of the university.

00:58:06.700 --> 00:58:11.130
Hundreds of alumni attended
in London, Los Angeles,

00:58:11.130 --> 00:58:12.790
and New York.

00:58:12.790 --> 00:58:15.560
Mark your calendars
for the series dates

00:58:15.560 --> 00:58:21.220
in Dallas, Seattle,
and Chicago next year.

00:58:21.220 --> 00:58:25.030
Recognizing the unique
reach of our club network,

00:58:25.030 --> 00:58:28.000
we held regional
conferences in Europe,

00:58:28.000 --> 00:58:32.350
South America, Asia, as
well as here in Cambridge,

00:58:32.350 --> 00:58:36.780
to connect our volunteers with
university leadership, faculty,

00:58:36.780 --> 00:58:39.470
and staff.

00:58:39.470 --> 00:58:43.540
Throughout my travels
this year, one theme

00:58:43.540 --> 00:58:47.340
emerged over and over.

00:58:47.340 --> 00:58:51.480
Attending Harvard, no
matter what school,

00:58:51.480 --> 00:58:54.960
was a transformative experience.

00:58:54.960 --> 00:58:59.000
When our alumni talk
about their time here,

00:58:59.000 --> 00:59:02.030
they talk about
being challenged,

00:59:02.030 --> 00:59:05.600
about looking
differently at the world,

00:59:05.600 --> 00:59:09.880
about making lifelong
friends, and about learning

00:59:09.880 --> 00:59:13.920
what is possible
to achieve in life.

00:59:13.920 --> 00:59:18.830
The role of the HAA is not only
to keep our alumni connected

00:59:18.830 --> 00:59:23.120
to the traditions of Harvard,
but also to keep people,

00:59:23.120 --> 00:59:26.630
near or far away,
days or decades

00:59:26.630 --> 00:59:30.010
removed, connected to
the vibrant university

00:59:30.010 --> 00:59:33.160
life that transformed them.

00:59:33.160 --> 00:59:39.050
It has been a great,
really great privilege

00:59:39.050 --> 00:59:44.010
and also pleasure to have served
in this role as the trustee

00:59:44.010 --> 00:59:47.680
of great traditions,
as well as laying plans

00:59:47.680 --> 00:59:49.570
to shape the future.

00:59:49.570 --> 00:59:50.140
Thank you.

01:00:00.640 --> 01:00:05.540
Now, in a most humbling
and inspiring tradition,

01:00:05.540 --> 01:00:08.890
we recognize the
two senior alumni

01:00:08.890 --> 01:00:13.300
who led the alumni
parade this afternoon.

01:00:13.300 --> 01:00:17.120
From the Radcliffe
class of 1937,

01:00:17.120 --> 01:00:21.210
Lillian Sugarman, who
turned 98 last year.

01:00:36.930 --> 01:00:43.170
And from the Harvard class
of 1939, Robert Rothschild,

01:00:43.170 --> 01:00:46.840
who celebrated his 95th
birthday this past January.

01:01:02.020 --> 01:01:04.880
Thank you for leading
our alumni parade.

01:01:04.880 --> 01:01:09.490
It is an honor to
celebrate you today.

01:01:09.490 --> 01:01:12.270
And now, it is my
privilege to present

01:01:12.270 --> 01:01:18.520
a member of the class of 1989,
elected by his classmates

01:01:18.520 --> 01:01:22.960
to serve as Chief Marshal
on the occasion of this,

01:01:22.960 --> 01:01:26.120
their 25th reunion.

01:01:26.120 --> 01:01:29.270
After this year's Chief
Marshal graduated,

01:01:29.270 --> 01:01:32.080
he helped start
Teach for America,

01:01:32.080 --> 01:01:35.810
along with a number
of other Harvard folk.

01:01:35.810 --> 01:01:38.630
For the past nine
years, he has led

01:01:38.630 --> 01:01:42.510
the Knowledge Is Power
Program Foundation, which

01:01:42.510 --> 01:01:47.790
oversees the national network
of KIPP public charter schools.

01:01:47.790 --> 01:01:51.680
Under his tenure, KIPP
has tripled in size,

01:01:51.680 --> 01:01:56.950
now serving more than 50,000
students across the country.

01:01:56.950 --> 01:02:00.620
In communities were roughly
half of the students drop out

01:02:00.620 --> 01:02:03.680
of high school, KIPP
is proving that it

01:02:03.680 --> 01:02:06.700
doesn't have to be this way.

01:02:06.700 --> 01:02:13.540
Among KIPP students, 93%
graduate high school and 83%

01:02:13.540 --> 01:02:14.540
go on to college.

01:02:24.370 --> 01:02:27.850
Today we recognize
a fellow alumnus

01:02:27.850 --> 01:02:30.740
who has committed his
life to helping students

01:02:30.740 --> 01:02:34.170
succeed despite great obstacles.

01:02:34.170 --> 01:02:37.405
Ladies and gentlemen, Chief
Marshal Richard Barth.

01:02:56.186 --> 01:03:01.060
And will the entire 25th
reunion class seated on stage

01:03:01.060 --> 01:03:03.673
this afternoon please
stand and be recognized?

01:03:18.780 --> 01:03:25.550
On June 30, I will, with some
reluctance and some relief,

01:03:25.550 --> 01:03:29.950
turn over the gavel to one
of the alumni association's

01:03:29.950 --> 01:03:33.080
most enthusiastic supporters.

01:03:33.080 --> 01:03:36.120
A member of the
college class of 1980

01:03:36.120 --> 01:03:39.550
and business school
class of 1984,

01:03:39.550 --> 01:03:42.250
Cynthia Torres has
given generously

01:03:42.250 --> 01:03:44.870
of her time and
energy from coast

01:03:44.870 --> 01:03:48.610
to coast and indeed
around the world.

01:03:48.610 --> 01:03:51.220
Hailing from
Southern California,

01:03:51.220 --> 01:03:54.040
she has led the
local club there,

01:03:54.040 --> 01:03:56.400
as well as being
active in career

01:03:56.400 --> 01:03:59.270
mentoring for current students.

01:03:59.270 --> 01:04:02.920
I am excited for
Cynthia, because I

01:04:02.920 --> 01:04:07.850
am sure she has no
idea just how much fun

01:04:07.850 --> 01:04:10.660
is in store for her next year.

01:04:10.660 --> 01:04:14.280
I know I leave the
HAA in great hands.

01:04:14.280 --> 01:04:18.111
Ms. President-elect Cynthia
Torres, will you please stand?

01:04:31.860 --> 01:04:36.900
Let me also recognize a
distinguished alumnus who

01:04:36.900 --> 01:04:43.700
will step down this June after
18 years of consecutive service

01:04:43.700 --> 01:04:49.360
on Harvard's governing
boards, six as an overseer,

01:04:49.360 --> 01:04:52.760
12 as a member of
the corporation,

01:04:52.760 --> 01:04:57.460
and the last four as the
corporation's senior fellow.

01:04:57.460 --> 01:05:00.680
Please join me in
applauding and thanking

01:05:00.680 --> 01:05:03.740
an extraordinary leader
in Harvard's governance

01:05:03.740 --> 01:05:06.320
over the past two decades,
Robert Reischauer.

01:05:22.420 --> 01:05:24.900
Next, it is my
pleasure to announce

01:05:24.900 --> 01:05:28.440
the results of this
spring's elections

01:05:28.440 --> 01:05:31.690
for Harvard's board of
overseers and the elected

01:05:31.690 --> 01:05:35.520
directors of the Harvard
Alumni Association.

01:05:35.520 --> 01:05:39.830
We are grateful to the entire
slate for their willingness

01:05:39.830 --> 01:05:43.100
to be of service to the
governance of Harvard.

01:05:43.100 --> 01:05:48.760
Additionally, thanks to all
you who voted and participated.

01:05:48.760 --> 01:05:53.140
Please hold your applause until
all the names in each category

01:05:53.140 --> 01:05:55.260
are announced.

01:05:55.260 --> 01:05:57.950
Five individuals
have been elected

01:05:57.950 --> 01:06:02.860
to the board of overseers
to serve for six years each.

01:06:02.860 --> 01:06:09.920
They are-- Michael Brown,
AB '83, JD '88, of Boston,

01:06:09.920 --> 01:06:17.560
Massachusetts; James Hildreth,
AB '79 of Davis, California;

01:06:17.560 --> 01:06:24.140
Jane Lubchenko, PhD '75,
of Corvallis, Oregon;

01:06:24.140 --> 01:06:31.960
Michael Lynton, AB '82, MBA
