01:11:01.540 --> 01:11:05.130
I'm now pleased to
present a special Harvard

01:11:05.130 --> 01:11:56.458
Medal to John P.
Reardon, Jr., AB 1960.

01:11:56.458 --> 01:11:58.480
How you doing?

01:11:58.480 --> 01:11:59.640
Want a speech?

01:11:59.640 --> 01:12:02.360
I'm hoping we didn't
give him a heart attack.

01:12:02.360 --> 01:12:03.230
You're OK?

01:12:03.230 --> 01:12:04.540
OK.

01:12:04.540 --> 01:12:09.410
From admissions to
athletics to alumni affairs,

01:12:09.410 --> 01:12:12.670
you have shaped the
Harvard we know and love,

01:12:12.670 --> 01:12:15.870
touching and changing
countless lives

01:12:15.870 --> 01:12:19.220
through your skillful
leadership and sage

01:12:19.220 --> 01:12:21.970
counsel, your
inpeccable judgment,

01:12:21.970 --> 01:12:25.050
and inimitable way with people.

01:12:25.050 --> 01:12:29.043
The whole Harvard family
salutes you and thanks you.

01:12:47.310 --> 01:12:50.900
I hope you can all
appreciate how much fun it

01:12:50.900 --> 01:12:53.410
was to keep a secret
from the man who

01:12:53.410 --> 01:12:57.200
knows everything about Harvard.

01:12:57.200 --> 01:13:01.200
And now, we will
actually hear from Jack

01:13:01.200 --> 01:13:05.940
in a video about why he
has dedicated and continues

01:13:05.940 --> 01:13:08.215
to dedicate his life to Harvard.

01:13:13.860 --> 01:13:16.320
Harvard's been from the
beginning very important

01:13:16.320 --> 01:13:17.180
in my life.

01:13:17.180 --> 01:13:21.630
I was surrounded by classmates
who, in the dining halls,

01:13:21.630 --> 01:13:24.450
in my living
situation, were always

01:13:24.450 --> 01:13:26.770
wanting to discuss
issues, issues in ways

01:13:26.770 --> 01:13:29.800
sometimes that I had never
given a lot of consideration.

01:13:29.800 --> 01:13:33.720
Plus faculty, professors,
who were really great.

01:13:33.720 --> 01:13:37.140
Professor Brzezinski
was my sophomore tutor.

01:13:37.140 --> 01:13:39.080
I remember at the
beginning of the year

01:13:39.080 --> 01:13:42.245
I was late to a meeting and
he said to me, I'm busy, too.

01:13:42.245 --> 01:13:44.550
If you can't be on time,
don't bother to come.

01:13:44.550 --> 01:13:45.830
And I got the point.

01:13:45.830 --> 01:13:48.596
That helped me to
be on time places.

01:13:48.596 --> 01:13:52.890
I think opening opportunities
to as many people who

01:13:52.890 --> 01:13:56.790
can take advantage of
what's here as possible

01:13:56.790 --> 01:13:57.860
is a great thing.

01:13:57.860 --> 01:14:01.620
I had a good example
of a person years

01:14:01.620 --> 01:14:05.060
ago who I recruited who was
a very good football player,

01:14:05.060 --> 01:14:08.020
listed in the Parade High School
All-Americans as a top player.

01:14:08.020 --> 01:14:09.580
We looked at those
kids one year,

01:14:09.580 --> 01:14:11.330
and this is the one person
who looked like maybe they

01:14:11.330 --> 01:14:12.370
could do Harvard work.

01:14:12.370 --> 01:14:14.234
Basically, he was an orphan.

01:14:14.234 --> 01:14:16.400
He was probably going to
go to Washington or Oregon.

01:14:16.400 --> 01:14:16.900
Forget him.

01:14:16.900 --> 01:14:18.560
I said, forget him?

01:14:18.560 --> 01:14:20.710
Let's get him back here.

01:14:20.710 --> 01:14:21.240
He came.

01:14:21.240 --> 01:14:22.730
He played three
years of football.

01:14:22.730 --> 01:14:23.600
He went to work.

01:14:23.600 --> 01:14:25.480
Very, very successful guy.

01:14:25.480 --> 01:14:28.320
And more recently, he
provided some money

01:14:28.320 --> 01:14:31.430
for the admissions office
to spend finding kids

01:14:31.430 --> 01:14:33.890
that you otherwise
wouldn't find.

01:14:33.890 --> 01:14:37.570
I think there are opportunities
like never before.

01:14:37.570 --> 01:14:41.710
I think Harvard was very
much a local institution

01:14:41.710 --> 01:14:44.830
50 years ago compared
to the way it is today.

01:14:44.830 --> 01:14:48.050
In the last 50 years,
throughout the university

01:14:48.050 --> 01:14:51.210
the diversity is huge,
tremendous change.

01:14:51.210 --> 01:14:54.270
It's just a very different
group of people here today

01:14:54.270 --> 01:14:56.870
than were here 50 years ago.

01:14:56.870 --> 01:15:00.970
We have great resources--
libraries, labs, and so forth--

01:15:00.970 --> 01:15:04.420
but the people that are drawn
here as students, and faculty,

01:15:04.420 --> 01:15:07.910
and staff want to
work with each other.

01:15:07.910 --> 01:15:10.330
And whatever they do, they
want to do it really well.

01:15:10.330 --> 01:15:12.870
I was lucky to meet
very special people

01:15:12.870 --> 01:15:14.450
through being at Harvard.

01:15:14.450 --> 01:15:16.510
And they certainly made
a difference to Harvard,

01:15:16.510 --> 01:15:18.370
and they made a
difference for my thinking

01:15:18.370 --> 01:15:21.340
about how to do things in life.

01:15:21.340 --> 01:15:24.650
Most alumni have had
ultimately good experiences.

01:15:24.650 --> 01:15:27.060
They want to see
the place strong

01:15:27.060 --> 01:15:32.570
and want to support it in ways
that can help it be strong.

01:15:32.570 --> 01:15:36.301
It also suggests that overall
people had good experiences

01:15:36.301 --> 01:15:38.550
that they think have made a
difference in their lives,

01:15:38.550 --> 01:15:41.240
and they want to see the
strength of the place continue.

01:15:41.240 --> 01:15:44.540
The one thing that is very
special, and a lot of people

01:15:44.540 --> 01:15:47.720
don't know it, but Harvard
is a very human place.

01:15:47.720 --> 01:15:50.300
You think of the bricks
and the concrete,

01:15:50.300 --> 01:15:52.120
but I think they do
support one another.

01:15:52.120 --> 01:15:54.600
I think it's an unusually
human place where

01:15:54.600 --> 01:15:56.580
people do care
about one another.

01:15:56.580 --> 01:16:00.130
It's been a spectacular
place to spend my life.

01:16:15.710 --> 01:16:18.680
I would like to
congratulate Jack

01:16:18.680 --> 01:16:21.710
and all of the
Harvard Medalists.

01:16:21.710 --> 01:16:25.890
Except for Jack, one of the best
things I got to do this year

01:16:25.890 --> 01:16:29.470
was to call each winner
and share the exciting news

01:16:29.470 --> 01:16:32.080
with them.

01:16:32.080 --> 01:16:38.150
So we are all citizens
of this great university.

01:16:38.150 --> 01:16:41.660
And our medalists today
are representative

01:16:41.660 --> 01:16:47.560
of the incredible dedication
of our alumni to Harvard.

01:16:47.560 --> 01:16:51.670
They are joined by a
core of tens of thousands

01:16:51.670 --> 01:16:56.100
of alumni who give of
their time and their talent

01:16:56.100 --> 01:16:58.220
to support Harvard.

01:16:58.220 --> 01:17:02.930
Our 234 Harvard clubs and
shared interest groups

01:17:02.930 --> 01:17:05.910
are run by volunteers.

01:17:05.910 --> 01:17:11.680
Over 15,000 alumni interview
applicants to Harvard College

01:17:11.680 --> 01:17:13.530
each year.

01:17:13.530 --> 01:17:20.040
Nearly 10,000 alumni and guests
return to campus university

01:17:20.040 --> 01:17:25.400
wide to attend
volunteer-run reunions.

01:17:25.400 --> 01:17:29.360
So as we celebrate
today, we also

01:17:29.360 --> 01:17:35.160
give thanks to our alumni and
friends, students and parents,

01:17:35.160 --> 01:17:37.530
faculty and staff.

01:17:37.530 --> 01:17:39.300
Thank you.

01:17:39.300 --> 01:17:44.620
Thank you for all that you
do for this great university.

01:17:44.620 --> 01:17:49.250
To all the volunteers committed
to connecting Harvard's alumni,

01:17:49.250 --> 01:17:54.200
thank you for all that you have
done this year and all that you

01:17:54.200 --> 01:17:57.470
will continue to do.

01:17:57.470 --> 01:18:02.060
This week, thousands of
alumni returned to campus

01:18:02.060 --> 01:18:07.600
in a great show of commitment
to the community of Harvard.

01:18:07.600 --> 01:18:12.250
Many come back for Harvard
and Radcliffe college reunions

01:18:12.250 --> 01:18:18.530
to reconnect with each other, to
experience the campus of today,

01:18:18.530 --> 01:18:23.090
and they show their support
through impressive levels

01:18:23.090 --> 01:18:24.950
of giving.

01:18:24.950 --> 01:18:27.940
Under the leadership
of many volunteers,

01:18:27.940 --> 01:18:31.120
including college reunion
committees and the class

01:18:31.120 --> 01:18:33.720
secretaries and
treasurers, we've

01:18:33.720 --> 01:18:38.950
drawn more than 6,500 alumni and
guests to Cambridge this week

01:18:38.950 --> 01:18:46.530
and helped generate nearly
5,400 gifts as of May 28.

01:18:46.530 --> 01:18:50.660
Today, we take a moment to
recognize some particularly

01:18:50.660 --> 01:18:54.860
impressive college
reunion efforts.

