01:24:58.380 --> 01:25:00.700
Would the Marshals
Senior Gift co-chairs

01:25:00.700 --> 01:25:02.510
please stand and be recognized?

01:25:02.510 --> 01:25:03.176
Congratulations.

01:25:19.580 --> 01:25:25.070
To all of you, our dedicated
citizens of Harvard,

01:25:25.070 --> 01:25:29.350
we continue to be inspired
by your volunteerism

01:25:29.350 --> 01:25:31.630
and philanthropy.

01:25:31.630 --> 01:25:32.510
Thank you.

01:25:32.510 --> 01:25:36.110
To celebrates these
amazing volunteers

01:25:36.110 --> 01:25:39.780
and our entire alumni
community, please

01:25:39.780 --> 01:25:44.670
join the Harvard University
Band and the commencement choir

01:25:44.670 --> 01:25:50.354
in their performance
of "Harvardiana."

01:28:00.660 --> 01:28:04.570
The band got to practice
that song a lot in Spokane

01:28:04.570 --> 01:28:07.210
this winter.

01:28:07.210 --> 01:28:12.470
Harvard's 21st president,
Charles W. Eliot,

01:28:12.470 --> 01:28:18.670
in his inaugural address
145 years ago said,

01:28:18.670 --> 01:28:25.886
quote, "The inertia of a massive
university is formidable.

01:28:25.886 --> 01:28:29.830
A good past is
positively dangerous

01:28:29.830 --> 01:28:33.760
if it makes us content
with the present

01:28:33.760 --> 01:28:38.620
and thus unprepared
for the future."

01:28:38.620 --> 01:28:43.550
Harvard's 28th president,
Drew Gilpin Faust,

01:28:43.550 --> 01:28:46.680
has demonstrated
dynamic leadership

01:28:46.680 --> 01:28:51.150
under which there
could be no inertia.

01:28:51.150 --> 01:28:54.410
In the past seven
years, President Faust

01:28:54.410 --> 01:29:00.160
has expanded financial aid to
improve access to a Harvard

01:29:00.160 --> 01:29:05.190
education for students from
all economic backgrounds,

01:29:05.190 --> 01:29:08.420
advocated for increased
federal funding

01:29:08.420 --> 01:29:12.450
for scientific
research, broadened

01:29:12.450 --> 01:29:19.020
the university's global reach,
raised the profile of the arts

01:29:19.020 --> 01:29:24.390
on campus, and this past
fall, launched the Harvard

01:29:24.390 --> 01:29:27.640
Campaign, an
ambitious fundraising

01:29:27.640 --> 01:29:32.270
campaign to position
Harvard, in her words,

01:29:32.270 --> 01:29:36.060
to seize an impatient future.

01:29:36.060 --> 01:29:40.500
Please join me in welcoming the
Lincoln Professor of History,

01:29:40.500 --> 01:29:43.662
Harvard's 28th president,
Drew Gilpin Faust.

01:29:49.566 --> 01:29:50.542
Thank you.

01:29:50.542 --> 01:29:51.042
Thank you.

01:29:54.970 --> 01:29:55.470
Goodness.

01:30:00.390 --> 01:30:01.858
Thank you.

01:30:01.858 --> 01:30:02.358
Thank you.

01:30:08.290 --> 01:30:12.710
Thank you all, and good
afternoon, alumni, graduates,

01:30:12.710 --> 01:30:15.990
families, friends,
honored guests.

01:30:15.990 --> 01:30:21.040
For seven years now, it has been
my assignment and my privilege

01:30:21.040 --> 01:30:25.350
to deliver an annual
report to our alumni

01:30:25.350 --> 01:30:30.150
and to serve as the warm-up act
for our distinguished speaker.

01:30:30.150 --> 01:30:32.600
Whether this is your
first opportunity

01:30:32.600 --> 01:30:35.980
to be part of these
exercises or your 50th,

01:30:35.980 --> 01:30:40.090
it's worth taking a minute
to soak in this place,

01:30:40.090 --> 01:30:43.310
its sheltering trees,
its familiar buildings,

01:30:43.310 --> 01:30:45.820
its enduring voices.

01:30:45.820 --> 01:30:49.180
In 1936, this part
of Harvard Yard

01:30:49.180 --> 01:30:54.190
was called Tercentenary
Theatre in recognition

01:30:54.190 --> 01:30:57.150
of Harvard's 300th birthday.

01:30:57.150 --> 01:30:59.910
It's a place where
giants have stood

01:30:59.910 --> 01:31:02.750
and history has been made.

01:31:02.750 --> 01:31:06.840
We were reminded this morning of
George Washington's adventures

01:31:06.840 --> 01:31:08.110
here.

01:31:08.110 --> 01:31:12.260
And from this stage in
1943, Winston Churchill

01:31:12.260 --> 01:31:15.660
addressed an overflow
crowd that included

01:31:15.660 --> 01:31:21.190
6,000 uniformed Harvard
students heading off to war.

01:31:21.190 --> 01:31:23.940
He said that he hoped
the young recruits would

01:31:23.940 --> 01:31:27.570
come to regard the British
soldiers and sailors they would

01:31:27.570 --> 01:31:32.040
soon fight alongside as
their brothers in arms.

01:31:32.040 --> 01:31:37.920
And he assured the audience that
we shall never tire nor weaken

01:31:37.920 --> 01:31:42.960
but march with you to
establish the reign of justice

01:31:42.960 --> 01:31:44.900
and of law.

01:31:44.900 --> 01:31:48.660
Four years later
in this same place,

01:31:48.660 --> 01:31:52.930
George Marshall introduced a
plan that aided reconstruction

01:31:52.930 --> 01:31:55.400
across war-stricken Europe.

01:31:55.400 --> 01:31:59.840
And he ended his speech
by asking, what is needed?

01:31:59.840 --> 01:32:02.310
What best can be done?

01:32:02.310 --> 01:32:05.240
What must be done?

01:32:05.240 --> 01:32:10.290
Here in 1998, Nelson Mandela
addressed an audience of 25,000

01:32:10.290 --> 01:32:13.180
and spoke of our shared future.

01:32:13.180 --> 01:32:16.600
The greatest single challenge
facing our globalized world,

01:32:16.600 --> 01:32:22.610
he said, is to combat and
eradicate its disparities.

01:32:22.610 --> 01:32:26.340
Ellen Johnson Sirleaf, the first
female head of state in Africa,

01:32:26.340 --> 01:32:30.290
stood here 13 years later
and encouraged graduates

01:32:30.290 --> 01:32:35.170
to resist cynicism
and to be fearless.

01:32:35.170 --> 01:32:39.920
Here on the terrible afternoon
of September 11, 2001,

01:32:39.920 --> 01:32:42.730
we gathered under
a cloudless sky

01:32:42.730 --> 01:32:47.340
to share our sadness, our
horror, and our disbelief.

01:32:47.340 --> 01:32:49.430
And here just three
years ago we marked

01:32:49.430 --> 01:32:53.290
Harvard's 375th
anniversary dancing

01:32:53.290 --> 01:32:57.530
in the mud of a
torrential downpour.

01:32:57.530 --> 01:33:01.320
Here, Franklin Delano Roosevelt
had celebrated Harvard's three

01:33:01.320 --> 01:33:07.000
centuries of accomplishment
in a comparably soaking rain.

01:33:07.000 --> 01:33:09.470
Here, J. K. Rowling
encouraged graduates

01:33:09.470 --> 01:33:12.980
to think themselves into
other people's places.

01:33:12.980 --> 01:33:18.190
And Conan O'Brien told them
that every failure is freeing.

01:33:18.190 --> 01:33:20.360
Here, honorary degrees
have been presented

01:33:20.360 --> 01:33:24.160
to Carl Jung, and Jean
Piaget, and Ellsworth Kelly,

01:33:24.160 --> 01:33:26.230
and Georgia O'Keeffe,
Helen Keller,

01:33:26.230 --> 01:33:32.080
and Martha Graham, Ravi Shankar,
and Leonard Bernstein, Joan

01:33:32.080 --> 01:33:35.960
Dideon, and Philip
Roth, Eric Kandel,

01:33:35.960 --> 01:33:41.880
and Elizabeth Blackburn, Bill
Gates, and Tim Berners-Lee.

01:33:41.880 --> 01:33:44.400
I remember feeling
awed by that history

01:33:44.400 --> 01:33:46.940
when I spoke here
at my installation

01:33:46.940 --> 01:33:50.160
as Harvard's 28th
president and when

01:33:50.160 --> 01:33:52.810
I reflected on what
has always seemed to me

01:33:52.810 --> 01:33:57.900
the essence of a university,
that among society's

01:33:57.900 --> 01:34:03.650
institutions it is uniquely
accountable to the past

01:34:03.650 --> 01:34:06.520
and to the future.

01:34:06.520 --> 01:34:10.730
Our accountability to the
past is all around us.

01:34:10.730 --> 01:34:15.030
Behind me stands Memorial
Church, a monument

01:34:15.030 --> 01:34:17.730
to Harvardians who gave
their lives at the Somme,

01:34:17.730 --> 01:34:22.830
and [INAUDIBLE] and Verdun
during World War I. Dedicated

01:34:22.830 --> 01:34:27.000
on Armistice Day in
1932, it represents

01:34:27.000 --> 01:34:31.620
Harvard's long tradition
of commitment to service.

01:34:31.620 --> 01:34:34.940
In front of me is
Widener Library,

01:34:34.940 --> 01:34:38.310
a gift from a
bereaved mother, named

01:34:38.310 --> 01:34:43.430
in honor of her son Harry who
perished aboard the Titanic,

01:34:43.430 --> 01:34:46.090
a library built to
advance the learning

01:34:46.090 --> 01:34:51.620
and discovery enabled by one
of the most diverse and broad

01:34:51.620 --> 01:34:54.490
collections in the world.

01:34:54.490 --> 01:34:57.770
Widener's 12 majestic
columns safeguard

01:34:57.770 --> 01:35:01.730
texts and manuscripts,
some centuries old,

01:35:01.730 --> 01:35:04.370
that are deployed
every day by scholars

01:35:04.370 --> 01:35:09.370
to help us interpret and
reinterpret the past.

01:35:09.370 --> 01:35:11.530
But this afternoon,
I would like to spend

01:35:11.530 --> 01:35:16.640
a few minutes considering our
accountability to the future,

01:35:16.640 --> 01:35:22.040
because these obligations must
be our compass to steer by,

01:35:22.040 --> 01:35:26.120
our common purpose, and
our shared commitment.

01:35:26.120 --> 01:35:32.200
What does Harvard-- what do
universities owe the future?

01:35:32.200 --> 01:35:36.660
First, we owe the world answers.

01:35:36.660 --> 01:35:41.300
Discovery is at the heart
of what universities do.

01:35:41.300 --> 01:35:44.240
Universities engage
faculty and students

01:35:44.240 --> 01:35:48.190
across a range of disciplines
in seeking solutions

01:35:48.190 --> 01:35:52.480
to problems that may have
seemed unsolvable, endeavoring

01:35:52.480 --> 01:35:56.870
to answer questions that
threaten to elude us.

01:35:56.870 --> 01:35:59.190
The scientific research
undertaken today

01:35:59.190 --> 01:36:02.910
at Harvard and tomorrow
by the students we educate

01:36:02.910 --> 01:36:07.870
has the capacity to improve
human lives in ways virtually

01:36:07.870 --> 01:36:11.450
unimaginable even
a generation ago.

01:36:11.450 --> 01:36:15.120
In this past year alone,
Harvard researchers

01:36:15.120 --> 01:36:18.810
have solved riddles related to
the treatment of Alzheimer's,

01:36:18.810 --> 01:36:22.700
the cost-effective production
of malaria vaccine,

01:36:22.700 --> 01:36:25.840
and the origins of the universe.

01:36:25.840 --> 01:36:28.030
Harvard researchers
have proposed answers

01:36:28.030 --> 01:36:31.400
to challenges as varied
as nuclear proliferation,

01:36:31.400 --> 01:36:36.270
American competitiveness, and
governance of the internet.

01:36:36.270 --> 01:36:40.510
We must continue to support
our answer seekers who

01:36:40.510 --> 01:36:45.110
work at the crossroads of the
theoretical and the applied,

01:36:45.110 --> 01:36:50.540
at the nexus of research, public
policy, and entrepreneurship.

01:36:50.540 --> 01:36:53.460
Together they will
shape our future

01:36:53.460 --> 01:36:57.390
and enhance our
understanding of the world.

01:36:57.390 --> 01:37:02.180
Second, we owe the
world questions.

01:37:02.180 --> 01:37:08.920
Just as questions yield answers,
answers yield questions.

01:37:08.920 --> 01:37:11.940
Human beings may long for
certainty, but as Oliver

01:37:11.940 --> 01:37:17.700
Wendell Holmes put it,
certainty generally is allusion,

01:37:17.700 --> 01:37:21.700
and repose is not
the destiny of man.

01:37:21.700 --> 01:37:24.320
Universities produce knowledge.

01:37:24.320 --> 01:37:27.890
They must also produced doubt.

01:37:27.890 --> 01:37:31.510
The pursuit of
truth is restless.

01:37:31.510 --> 01:37:35.610
We search for answers not by
following prescribed paths

01:37:35.610 --> 01:37:38.090
but by finding the
right questions,

01:37:38.090 --> 01:37:41.020
by answering one question
with another question,

01:37:41.020 --> 01:37:45.110
by nurturing a state of mind
that is flexible and alert,

01:37:45.110 --> 01:37:48.490
dissatisfied and imaginative.

01:37:48.490 --> 01:37:52.590
It's what universities
are designed to do.

01:37:52.590 --> 01:37:56.610
In an essay in Harvard Magazine,
one of today's graduates,

01:37:56.610 --> 01:37:59.660
Cherone Dugan,
wrote about seeking

01:37:59.660 --> 01:38:04.040
what she called an
education of questions.

01:38:04.040 --> 01:38:08.660
I hope we have indeed
given her that.

01:38:08.660 --> 01:38:11.130
Questions are the
foundation for progress,

01:38:11.130 --> 01:38:13.310
for ensuring that
the world transcends

01:38:13.310 --> 01:38:16.620
where we are now,
what we know now.

01:38:16.620 --> 01:38:18.790
And questions are
also the foundation

01:38:18.790 --> 01:38:24.430
for a third obligation that we
as universities owe the future.

01:38:24.430 --> 01:38:27.810
We owe the future meaning.

01:38:27.810 --> 01:38:29.810
Universities must
nurture the ability

01:38:29.810 --> 01:38:33.140
to interpret, to make
critical judgments,

01:38:33.140 --> 01:38:36.700
to dare to ask the biggest
questions, the ones that

01:38:36.700 --> 01:38:40.480
reach well beyond the
immediate and the instrumental.

01:38:40.480 --> 01:38:44.660
We must stimulate the
appetite for curiosity.

01:38:44.660 --> 01:38:48.330
We find many of these
questions in the humanities.

01:38:48.330 --> 01:38:49.700
What is good?

01:38:49.700 --> 01:38:51.400
What is just?

01:38:51.400 --> 01:38:53.920
How do we know what is true?

01:38:53.920 --> 01:38:56.870
But we find them in
the sciences, as well.

01:38:56.870 --> 01:39:00.580
Can there be any question more
profound, more fundamental,

01:39:00.580 --> 01:39:04.970
than to ask about the
origins of the universe?

01:39:04.970 --> 01:39:07.730
How did we get here?

01:39:07.730 --> 01:39:10.090
Questions like these
can be unsettling

01:39:10.090 --> 01:39:14.070
and they can make universities
unsettling places,

01:39:14.070 --> 01:39:16.090
but that, too, is
an essential part

01:39:16.090 --> 01:39:21.430
of what we owe the future-- the
promise to combat complacency,

01:39:21.430 --> 01:39:23.410
to challenge the
present in order

01:39:23.410 --> 01:39:28.530
to prepare for what is to come,
to shape the present in service

01:39:28.530 --> 01:39:32.730
of an uncertain and
yet impatient future.

01:39:32.730 --> 01:39:34.910
We owe the future answers.

01:39:34.910 --> 01:39:36.650
We owe the future questions.

01:39:36.650 --> 01:39:38.880
We owe the future meaning.

01:39:38.880 --> 01:39:41.200
The Harvard Campaign
launched last September

01:39:41.200 --> 01:39:44.490
will help us fulfill these
obligations and pay our debt

01:39:44.490 --> 01:39:48.880
to the future, just as the
gifts of previous generations

01:39:48.880 --> 01:39:51.580
anchor us here today.

01:39:51.580 --> 01:39:54.660
As today's ceremonies
so powerfully remind us,

01:39:54.660 --> 01:39:58.090
we also owe the future
the men and women

01:39:58.090 --> 01:40:01.440
who are prepared to ask
questions and seek answers

01:40:01.440 --> 01:40:04.770
and search for meaning
for decades to come.

01:40:04.770 --> 01:40:07.540
Today we send some
6,500 graduates

01:40:07.540 --> 01:40:11.260
into the world to be teachers
and lawyers, scientists

01:40:11.260 --> 01:40:15.440
and physicians, poets and
planners and public servants,

01:40:15.440 --> 01:40:17.890
and as our speaker this
morning reminded us,

01:40:17.890 --> 01:40:21.480
to be in their own
ways revolutionaries,

01:40:21.480 --> 01:40:24.640
ready to take on everything
from water scarcity

01:40:24.640 --> 01:40:28.190
to virtual currency
to community policing.

01:40:28.190 --> 01:40:31.040
We must continue to
invest in financial aid

01:40:31.040 --> 01:40:34.540
to attract and support
the talented students who

01:40:34.540 --> 01:40:36.540
can build our future.

01:40:36.540 --> 01:40:39.630
And also, we must invest
in supporting the teaching

01:40:39.630 --> 01:40:41.590
and learning that
ensures the fullest

01:40:41.590 --> 01:40:46.190
development of their
capacities in a changing world.

01:40:46.190 --> 01:40:50.370
If we fulfill our
obligations, today's graduates

01:40:50.370 --> 01:40:55.710
will have found the education
of questions Cherone described,

01:40:55.710 --> 01:41:02.920
a place where, as she put it,
ceilings are made only of sky.

01:41:02.920 --> 01:41:03.870
But look around you.

01:41:03.870 --> 01:41:05.870
We're there.

01:41:05.870 --> 01:41:11.030
This place is a theater
without walls, without a roof,

01:41:11.030 --> 01:41:13.030
and without limits.

01:41:13.030 --> 01:41:17.910
It's a place where extraordinary
individuals have preceded us,

01:41:17.910 --> 01:41:22.010
a place that must encourage
our graduates of today

01:41:22.010 --> 01:41:26.570
and all the years passed to
emulate those women and men,

01:41:26.570 --> 01:41:29.490
to look skyward and to soar.

01:41:29.490 --> 01:41:30.972
Thank you very much.

01:41:47.090 --> 01:41:49.160
Thank you, President Faust.

01:41:49.160 --> 01:41:52.360
There is no question that
we are fortunate to have you

01:41:52.360 --> 01:41:53.140
as our leader.

01:41:53.140 --> 01:41:54.830
Thank you, Kate.

01:41:54.830 --> 01:41:59.590
To honor the contributions
of Radcliffe College and it's

01:41:59.590 --> 01:42:04.130
alumni and to mark its
historical significance

01:42:04.130 --> 01:42:08.510
for men and women alike,
please stand and join

01:42:08.510 --> 01:42:11.530
in singing Radcliffe's
alma mater,

01:42:11.530 --> 01:42:13.760
"Radcliffe, Now We
Rise to Greet Thee."

01:42:13.760 --> 01:42:16.087
The words are in your program.

01:43:48.960 --> 01:43:52.720
This afternoon's
commencement speaker

01:43:52.720 --> 01:43:55.980
is known around the world.

01:43:55.980 --> 01:44:00.730
If you work in finance, you
are aware of what a Bloomberg

01:44:00.730 --> 01:44:05.510
Terminal is and the unique
color-coded keyboard that

01:44:05.510 --> 01:44:07.460
comes with it.

01:44:07.460 --> 01:44:11.500
If you live in or
near a city, you

01:44:11.500 --> 01:44:16.250
probably follow mayoral politics
and have heard something

01:44:16.250 --> 01:44:19.970
about the former mayor
of New York City.

01:44:19.970 --> 01:44:23.410
And if you are here with an
interest in public health,

01:44:23.410 --> 01:44:27.950
the arts, the
environment, or education,

01:44:27.950 --> 01:44:31.450
then you know how his
philanthropic support

01:44:31.450 --> 01:44:34.900
is focused around impact.

01:44:34.900 --> 01:44:38.600
After growing up a little
over five miles from here

01:44:38.600 --> 01:44:41.900
in Medford, Michael
Bloomberg graduated

01:44:41.900 --> 01:44:46.300
from Johns Hopkins
in 1964 with a degree

01:44:46.300 --> 01:44:48.730
in electrical engineering.

01:44:48.730 --> 01:44:52.860
After college, he attended
Harvard Business School and in

01:44:52.860 --> 01:44:59.090
1966 was hired by a Wall
Street firm, Solomon Brothers,

01:44:59.090 --> 01:45:02.480
for an entry-level job.

01:45:02.480 --> 01:45:07.700
He left in 1981 to found
Bloomberg LP, which

01:45:07.700 --> 01:45:11.380
he led for 20 years.

01:45:11.380 --> 01:45:15.840
In 2001, he ran for
mayor of New York

01:45:15.840 --> 01:45:21.240
and was elected two months
after the 9/11 tragedy.

01:45:21.240 --> 01:45:24.410
During his three
terms in office,

01:45:24.410 --> 01:45:30.400
he focused on public health,
combating crime, gun control,

01:45:30.400 --> 01:45:33.760
the environment, and
many other issues

01:45:33.760 --> 01:45:36.590
important to New Yorkers.

01:45:36.590 --> 01:45:40.160
Throughout his entire
career, Michael Bloomberg

01:45:40.160 --> 01:45:42.853
has also been an
active philanthropist.

01:45:45.530 --> 01:45:48.280
As a philanthropist,
Bloomberg has

01:45:48.280 --> 01:45:51.140
been realistic
about how to tackle

01:45:51.140 --> 01:45:54.840
large problems around the world.

01:45:54.840 --> 01:45:57.700
In business, he has
shown that there

01:45:57.700 --> 01:46:01.160
are many ways to
make a difference.

01:46:01.160 --> 01:46:04.070
As mayor, he
understood that he is

01:46:04.070 --> 01:46:08.520
responsible for
delivering results.

01:46:08.520 --> 01:46:13.800
There is nobody better qualified
to address our alumni today

01:46:13.800 --> 01:46:18.360
than Mr. Michael Bloomberg,
founder of Bloomberg LP,

01:46:18.360 --> 01:46:22.000
108th mayor of New York
City, and philanthropist.

01:46:35.257 --> 01:46:37.740
Thank you.

01:46:37.740 --> 01:46:38.750
Thank you, Katie.

01:46:38.750 --> 01:46:41.530
And thank you to President
Faust, and the Fellows

01:46:41.530 --> 01:46:44.810
of Harvard College,
the Board of Overseers,

01:46:44.810 --> 01:46:48.470
and all of the faculty,
alumni, and students

01:46:48.470 --> 01:46:52.090
who have welcomed
me back to campus.

01:46:52.090 --> 01:46:55.270
I am excited to be here,
not only to address

01:46:55.270 --> 01:46:59.170
the distinguished graduates and
alumni at Harvard University's

01:46:59.170 --> 01:47:03.770
363rd commencement,
but most importantly

01:47:03.770 --> 01:47:09.972
to stand in the exact spot
where Oprah stood last year.

01:47:09.972 --> 01:47:12.427
O-M-G.

01:47:15.380 --> 01:47:18.000
Let me begin with the
first order of business.

01:47:18.000 --> 01:47:21.970
Let's have a big round of
applause for the class of 2014.

01:47:21.970 --> 01:47:22.840
They've earned it.

01:47:35.060 --> 01:47:38.130
Now, excited as
these graduates are,

01:47:38.130 --> 01:47:40.490
they are probably
even more exhausted

01:47:40.490 --> 01:47:42.300
after the past few weeks.

01:47:42.300 --> 01:47:47.400
And parents, I am not
referring to their final exams.

01:47:47.400 --> 01:47:51.280
I'm talking about the Senior
Olympics, the Last Chance

01:47:51.280 --> 01:47:55.380
Dance, and the booze cruise--
I mean the midnight cruise.

01:47:55.380 --> 01:47:58.970
Anyways, this year has
been exciting on campus.

01:47:58.970 --> 01:48:02.060
Harvard beat Yale for
the seventh straight time

01:48:02.060 --> 01:48:02.560
in football.

01:48:08.210 --> 01:48:12.390
The men's basketball team went
to the second round of the NCAA

01:48:12.390 --> 01:48:14.420
tournament for the
second straight year.

01:48:17.650 --> 01:48:22.920
And the men's squash team won
the national championship.

01:48:22.920 --> 01:48:26.397
Who'd have thunk it?

01:48:26.397 --> 01:48:27.230
Who'd have thunk it?

01:48:27.230 --> 01:48:30.600
Harvard, an athletic powerhouse.

01:48:30.600 --> 01:48:33.870
Pretty soon, Drew, they're going
to be asking whether you have

01:48:33.870 --> 01:48:38.820
academics to go along with
your academic programs.

01:48:38.820 --> 01:48:40.660
Now, my personal
connection to Harvard

01:48:40.660 --> 01:48:44.380
began back in 1964
when I graduated

01:48:44.380 --> 01:48:47.430
from Johns Hopkins in
Baltimore and matriculated here

01:48:47.430 --> 01:48:49.080
at the B school.

01:48:49.080 --> 01:48:51.750
You're probably asking
yourself, or maybe whispering

01:48:51.750 --> 01:48:53.940
to the person next
to you, how did

01:48:53.940 --> 01:48:56.540
he ever get into
Harvard Business School,

01:48:56.540 --> 01:49:01.040
particularly since his stellar
academic record where he always

01:49:01.040 --> 01:49:03.446
made the top half of
the class possible?

01:49:06.200 --> 01:49:07.820
I have no idea.

01:49:07.820 --> 01:49:10.090
The only people who were
more surprised than me

01:49:10.090 --> 01:49:12.550
were my professors.

01:49:12.550 --> 01:49:15.080
Anyways, here I am
back in Cambridge,

01:49:15.080 --> 01:49:16.580
and I've noticed
a few things have

01:49:16.580 --> 01:49:19.270
changed since I
was a student here.

01:49:19.270 --> 01:49:22.860
Elsie's, a sandwich spot I
used to love near the square,

01:49:22.860 --> 01:49:27.040
is now a burrito shop.

01:49:27.040 --> 01:49:29.850
The Wursthaus, which had
great beer and sausage,

01:49:29.850 --> 01:49:35.490
is now an artisanal
gastropub, whatever that is.

01:49:35.490 --> 01:49:37.750
And the old Holyoke
Center is now

01:49:37.750 --> 01:49:41.010
named the Smith Campus Center.

01:49:41.010 --> 01:49:43.450
Don't you just hate it
when alumni put their names

01:49:43.450 --> 01:49:46.390
all over everything?

01:49:46.390 --> 01:49:47.870
I was thinking
about this morning

01:49:47.870 --> 01:49:49.520
as I walked into
the Bloomberg Center

01:49:49.520 --> 01:49:53.930
on the Harvard Business School
campus across the river.

01:49:53.930 --> 01:49:56.530
But the good news
is, Harvard remains

01:49:56.530 --> 01:50:00.350
what it was when I first
arrived on campus 50 years ago,

01:50:00.350 --> 01:50:03.500
America's most
prestigious university.

01:50:03.500 --> 01:50:05.660
And like other
great universities,

01:50:05.660 --> 01:50:08.730
it lies at the heart of
the American experiment

01:50:08.730 --> 01:50:10.570
in democracy.

01:50:10.570 --> 01:50:13.770
Their purpose is not
only to advance knowledge

01:50:13.770 --> 01:50:17.580
but to advance the
ideals of our nation.

01:50:17.580 --> 01:50:19.380
Great universities
are places where

01:50:19.380 --> 01:50:23.160
people of all backgrounds,
holding all beliefs,

01:50:23.160 --> 01:50:27.300
pursuing all questions, can
come to study and debate

01:50:27.300 --> 01:50:30.930
their ideas freely and openly.

01:50:30.930 --> 01:50:33.600
And today I'd like to talk
to you about how important it

01:50:33.600 --> 01:50:37.520
is for that freedom to exist
for everyone, no matter

01:50:37.520 --> 01:50:41.950
how strongly we may disagree
with another's viewpoint.

01:50:41.950 --> 01:50:44.990
Tolerance for other
people's ideas

01:50:44.990 --> 01:50:48.260
and the freedom to
express your own

01:50:48.260 --> 01:50:52.000
are inseparable values
at great universities.

01:50:52.000 --> 01:50:55.300
Joined together, they
form a sacred trust

01:50:55.300 --> 01:50:59.000
that holds the basis of
our democratic society.

01:50:59.000 --> 01:51:01.570
But let me tell you,
that trust is perpetually

01:51:01.570 --> 01:51:07.450
vulnerable to the tyrannical
tendencies of monarchs, mobs,

01:51:07.450 --> 01:51:09.230
and majorities.

01:51:09.230 --> 01:51:13.290
And lately we've seen those
tendencies manifest themselves

01:51:13.290 --> 01:51:18.360
too often, both on college
campuses and in our society.

01:51:18.360 --> 01:51:20.000
That's the bad news.

01:51:20.000 --> 01:51:22.520
And unfortunately,
I think both Harvard

01:51:22.520 --> 01:51:26.820
and my own city, New York, have
been witnesses to this trend.

01:51:26.820 --> 01:51:28.890
First, for New York City.

01:51:28.890 --> 01:51:31.590
Several years ago,
as you may remember,

01:51:31.590 --> 01:51:34.530
some people tried to stop
the development of a mosque

01:51:34.530 --> 01:51:37.790
a few blocks from the
World Trade Center site.

01:51:37.790 --> 01:51:40.210
It was an emotional
issue, and polls

01:51:40.210 --> 01:51:42.560
showed that 2/3
of Americans were

01:51:42.560 --> 01:51:45.270
against a mosque
being built there.

01:51:45.270 --> 01:51:48.570
Even the Anti-Defamation
League, widely regarded

01:51:48.570 --> 01:51:52.210
as the country's most ardent
defender of religious freedom,

01:51:52.210 --> 01:51:55.370
declared its opposition
to the project.

01:51:55.370 --> 01:51:58.780
The opponents held rallies
and demonstrations.

01:51:58.780 --> 01:52:01.020
They denounced the
developers, and they

01:52:01.020 --> 01:52:05.140
demanded that city government
stop its construction.

01:52:05.140 --> 01:52:08.060
That was their right, and
we protected their right

01:52:08.060 --> 01:52:09.540
to protest.

01:52:09.540 --> 01:52:11.860
But they could not
have been more wrong,

01:52:11.860 --> 01:52:15.700
and we refused to cave
in to those demands.

01:52:15.700 --> 01:52:18.280
The idea that government
would single out

01:52:18.280 --> 01:52:22.760
a particular religion and
block its believers, and only

01:52:22.760 --> 01:52:25.530
its believers, from
building a house of worship

01:52:25.530 --> 01:52:29.000
in a particular area is
diametrically opposed

01:52:29.000 --> 01:52:32.860
to the moral principles that
gave rise to our great nation

01:52:32.860 --> 01:52:35.090
and the constitutional
protections that

01:52:35.090 --> 01:52:36.539
have sustained it.

01:52:48.150 --> 01:52:51.990
Our union of 50 states
rests on the union

01:52:51.990 --> 01:52:56.350
of two values,
freedom and tolerance.

01:52:56.350 --> 01:52:59.730
And it is that union of
values that the terrorists who

01:52:59.730 --> 01:53:07.240
attacked us on September 11,
2001 and on April 15, 2013

01:53:07.240 --> 01:53:09.160
found most threatening.

01:53:09.160 --> 01:53:12.770
To them, we were
a godless country.

01:53:12.770 --> 01:53:15.430
But in fact, there
is no country that

01:53:15.430 --> 01:53:18.680
protects the core of every
faith and philosophy known

01:53:18.680 --> 01:53:22.070
to humankind, free will,
more than the United

01:53:22.070 --> 01:53:22.820
States of America.

01:53:29.180 --> 01:53:32.070
And that protection,
however, rests

01:53:32.070 --> 01:53:35.040
upon our constant vigilance.

01:53:35.040 --> 01:53:37.240
We like to think that the
principle of separation

01:53:37.240 --> 01:53:39.130
of church and state is settled.

01:53:39.130 --> 01:53:41.860
It is not, and it never will be.

01:53:41.860 --> 01:53:44.860
It's up to us to
guard it fiercely

01:53:44.860 --> 01:53:47.860
and to ensure that
equality under the law

01:53:47.860 --> 01:53:51.690
means equality under
the law for everyone.

01:53:51.690 --> 01:53:55.200
If you want the freedom
to worship as you wish,

01:53:55.200 --> 01:53:59.690
to speak as you wish, and
to marry whom you wish,

01:53:59.690 --> 01:54:06.030
you must tolerate my freedom to
do so or not to do so, as well.

01:54:06.030 --> 01:54:08.106
Now, what I do may offend you.

01:54:08.106 --> 01:54:12.280
You may find my actions
immoral or unjust,

01:54:12.280 --> 01:54:15.640
but attempting to restrict
my freedoms in ways

01:54:15.640 --> 01:54:20.590
that you would not restrict your
own leads only to injustice.

01:54:20.590 --> 01:54:24.780
We cannot deny others the rights
and privileges that we demand

01:54:24.780 --> 01:54:26.360
for ourselves.

01:54:26.360 --> 01:54:28.830
And that is true
in cities, and it

01:54:28.830 --> 01:54:33.080
is no less true at universities
where the forces of repression

01:54:33.080 --> 01:54:35.270
appear to be stronger
now, I think,

01:54:35.270 --> 01:54:39.830
than they have been at
any time since the 1950s.

01:54:39.830 --> 01:54:44.108
When I was growing up, US
Senator-- yes, you can applaud.

01:54:48.930 --> 01:54:51.660
When I was growing up,
US Senator Joe McCarthy

01:54:51.660 --> 01:54:56.790
was asking, are you now
or have you ever been?

01:54:56.790 --> 01:54:59.830
He was attempting to
repress and criminalize

01:54:59.830 --> 01:55:04.040
those who sympathized with an
economic system that was even

01:55:04.040 --> 01:55:05.870
then failing.

01:55:05.870 --> 01:55:10.030
McCarthy's Red Scare
destroyed thousands of lives,

01:55:10.030 --> 01:55:12.370
but what was he so afraid of?

01:55:12.370 --> 01:55:16.050
An idea, in this case
communism, that he and others

01:55:16.050 --> 01:55:18.060
deemed dangerous?

01:55:18.060 --> 01:55:20.310
But he was right
about one thing.

01:55:20.310 --> 01:55:22.930
Ideas can be dangerous.

01:55:22.930 --> 01:55:25.120
They can change society.

01:55:25.120 --> 01:55:27.130
They can upend traditions.

01:55:27.130 --> 01:55:29.360
They can start revolutions.

01:55:29.360 --> 01:55:32.250
And that's why throughout
history, those in authority

01:55:32.250 --> 01:55:34.880
have tried to repress
the ideas that

01:55:34.880 --> 01:55:39.770
threaten their power, their
religion, their ideology,

01:55:39.770 --> 01:55:42.350
or their reelection chances.

01:55:42.350 --> 01:55:45.790
This was true for
Socrates and Galileo.

01:55:45.790 --> 01:55:50.410
It was true for Nelson
Mandela and Vaclav Havel.

01:55:50.410 --> 01:55:53.780
And it has been true for
Ai Weiwei, Pussy Riot,

01:55:53.780 --> 01:55:57.420
and the kids who made the
"Happy" video in Iran.

01:55:57.420 --> 01:56:02.590
Repressing free expression
is a natural human weakness,

01:56:02.590 --> 01:56:06.240
and it is up to us to
fight it at every turn.

01:56:06.240 --> 01:56:10.480
Intolerance of ideas, whether
liberal or conservative,

01:56:10.480 --> 01:56:14.510
is antithetical to individual
rights and free societies.

01:56:14.510 --> 01:56:18.020
And it is no less antithetical
to great universities

01:56:18.020 --> 01:56:20.500
and first-rate scholarships.

01:56:20.500 --> 01:56:23.810
Now, there is an idea floating
around college campuses,

01:56:23.810 --> 01:56:26.240
including here at
Harvard, I think,

01:56:26.240 --> 01:56:29.790
that scholars should be funded
only if their work conforms

01:56:29.790 --> 01:56:33.000
to a particular view of justice.

01:56:33.000 --> 01:56:36.220
There's a word for
that idea-- censorship.

01:56:36.220 --> 01:56:40.130
And it is just a modern
form of McCarthyism.

01:56:40.130 --> 01:56:41.900
Think about the irony.

01:56:41.900 --> 01:56:45.200
In the 1950s, the right
wing was attempting

01:56:45.200 --> 01:56:48.180
to repress left wing ideas.

01:56:48.180 --> 01:56:50.810
Today on many
college campuses, it

01:56:50.810 --> 01:56:54.240
is liberals trying to
repress conservative ideas,

01:56:54.240 --> 01:56:56.300
even as conservative
faculty members

01:56:56.300 --> 01:56:59.130
are at risk of becoming
an endangered species.

01:56:59.130 --> 01:57:02.650
And that is probably
nowhere more true

01:57:02.650 --> 01:57:05.280
than it is here
in the Ivy League.

01:57:05.280 --> 01:57:09.345
In the 2012 presidential race,
according to federal-- yes,

01:57:09.345 --> 01:57:09.845
thank you.

01:57:13.270 --> 01:57:17.740
In the 2012 presidential race,
according to Federal Election

01:57:17.740 --> 01:57:22.630
Commission data, 96% of
all campaign contributions

01:57:22.630 --> 01:57:27.390
from Ivy League faculty and
employees went to Barack Obama.

01:57:27.390 --> 01:57:27.890
96%.

01:57:31.320 --> 01:57:34.415
There was more disagreement
among the old Soviet Politburo

01:57:34.415 --> 01:57:37.990
than there was among
Ivy League donors.

01:57:37.990 --> 01:57:40.330
And that statistic should
give us some pause.

01:57:40.330 --> 01:57:42.320
And I say that as
someone who endorsed

01:57:42.320 --> 01:57:44.530
President Obama for reelection.

01:57:44.530 --> 01:57:46.360
Because let me
tell you something.

01:57:46.360 --> 01:57:50.610
Neither party has a monopoly
on truth or God on its side.

01:57:56.200 --> 01:58:00.750
When 96% of Ivy League
donors prefer one candidate

01:58:00.750 --> 01:58:03.910
to another, you really have to
wonder whether the students are

01:58:03.910 --> 01:58:06.750
being exposed to the
diversity of views

01:58:06.750 --> 01:58:09.590
that a great university
should offer.

01:58:09.590 --> 01:58:13.820
Diversity of gender, ethnicity,
and orientation is important,

01:58:13.820 --> 01:58:17.560
but a university cannot be great
if it's faculty is politically

01:58:17.560 --> 01:58:19.070
homogeneous.

01:58:19.070 --> 01:58:25.310
In fact, the whole purpose
of-- in fact, the whole purpose

01:58:25.310 --> 01:58:28.260
of granting tenure
to professors is

01:58:28.260 --> 01:58:31.120
to ensure that they feel
free to conduct research

01:58:31.120 --> 01:58:33.930
on ideas that run
afoul of university

01:58:33.930 --> 01:58:36.870
politics and societal norms.

01:58:36.870 --> 01:58:39.540
When tenure was
created, it mostly

01:58:39.540 --> 01:58:44.860
protected liberals whose ideas
ran against conservative norms.

01:58:44.860 --> 01:58:47.400
Today, if tenure is
going to continue,

01:58:47.400 --> 01:58:49.370
it must also protect
conservatives

01:58:49.370 --> 01:58:52.490
whose ideas run up
against liberal norms.

01:58:52.490 --> 01:58:56.070
Otherwise, university
research and the professors

01:58:56.070 --> 01:58:58.660
who conduct it will
lose credibility.

01:58:58.660 --> 01:59:02.440
Great universities must not
become predictably partisan,

01:59:02.440 --> 01:59:05.750
and a liberal arts
education must not

01:59:05.750 --> 01:59:08.970
be an education in
the art of liberalism.

01:59:08.970 --> 01:59:12.870
The role of universities is
not to promote an ideology.

01:59:12.870 --> 01:59:17.110
It is to provide scholars and
students with a neutral forum

01:59:17.110 --> 01:59:19.930
for researching
and debating issues

01:59:19.930 --> 01:59:22.600
without tipping the
scales in one direction

01:59:22.600 --> 01:59:25.380
or repressing unpopular views.

01:59:25.380 --> 01:59:28.600
Requiring scholars and
commencement speakers,

01:59:28.600 --> 01:59:32.520
for that matter, to conform
to certain political standards

01:59:32.520 --> 01:59:35.326
undermines the whole
purpose of a university.

01:59:46.330 --> 01:59:49.610
This spring it has been serving
to see a number of college

01:59:49.610 --> 01:59:53.300
commencement speakers withdrawal
or have their invitations

01:59:53.300 --> 01:59:56.390
rescinded after
protests from students

01:59:56.390 --> 01:59:59.640
and, to me, shockingly
from senior faculty

01:59:59.640 --> 02:00:02.250
and administrators who
should know better.

02:00:02.250 --> 02:00:06.860
It happened at Brandeis,
Haverford, Rutgers, and Smith.

02:00:06.860 --> 02:00:09.780
And last year, it happened at
Swarthmore and Johns Hopkins,

02:00:09.780 --> 02:00:11.800
I'm sorry to say.

02:00:11.800 --> 02:00:15.710
In each of these cases,
liberals silenced a voice,

02:00:15.710 --> 02:00:19.010
and they denied an honorary
degree to individuals

02:00:19.010 --> 02:00:22.120
that they deemed
politically objectionable.

02:00:22.120 --> 02:00:25.024
This is an outrage, and we
must not let it continue.

02:00:32.780 --> 02:00:36.950
If the university thinks twice
before inviting a commencement

02:00:36.950 --> 02:00:39.790
speaker because of
his or her politics,

02:00:39.790 --> 02:00:44.660
censorship and conformity,
the mortal enemies of freedom,

02:00:44.660 --> 02:00:45.730
win out.

02:00:45.730 --> 02:00:48.580
And sadly, it's not
just commencement season

02:00:48.580 --> 02:00:51.180
when speakers are censored.

02:00:51.180 --> 02:00:53.750
Last fall when I was
still in City Hall,

02:00:53.750 --> 02:00:55.490
our police commissioner
was invited

02:00:55.490 --> 02:00:59.740
to deliver a lecture at
another Ivy League institution,

02:00:59.740 --> 02:01:02.970
but he was unable to do so
because students shouted him

02:01:02.970 --> 02:01:04.120
down.

02:01:04.120 --> 02:01:06.970
Isn't the purpose
of the university

02:01:06.970 --> 02:01:10.100
to stir discussion,
not silence it?

02:01:10.100 --> 02:01:12.410
What were the students
afraid of hearing?

02:01:12.410 --> 02:01:14.580
And why did
administrators not step in

02:01:14.580 --> 02:01:17.880
to prevent the mob
from silencing speech?

02:01:17.880 --> 02:01:21.960
And did anyone consider that
it is morally and pedagogically

02:01:21.960 --> 02:01:26.120
wrong to deprive other students
the chance to hear the speech?

02:01:26.120 --> 02:01:28.680
Now, I'm sure all
of today's graduates

02:01:28.680 --> 02:01:31.860
have read John Stuart
Mill's On Liberty,

02:01:31.860 --> 02:01:35.340
but just let me read a
short passage from it.

02:01:35.340 --> 02:01:39.580
Quote, "the particular evil
of silencing the expression

02:01:39.580 --> 02:01:43.510
of an opinion is that it
is robbing the human race,

02:01:43.510 --> 02:01:47.110
posterity, as well as the
existing generation, those

02:01:47.110 --> 02:01:49.140
who dissent from
the opinion still

02:01:49.140 --> 02:01:51.500
more than those who hold it."

02:01:51.500 --> 02:01:54.270
He continued, "if
the opinion is right,

02:01:54.270 --> 02:01:56.130
they are deprived
of the opportunity

02:01:56.130 --> 02:01:59.020
of exchanging error for truth.

02:01:59.020 --> 02:02:01.620
If wrong, they lose
what is almost as

02:02:01.620 --> 02:02:04.900
great a benefit, the clear
perception and livelier

02:02:04.900 --> 02:02:09.710
impression of truth produced
by its collision with error."

02:02:09.710 --> 02:02:11.410
Now, Mill would
have been horrified

02:02:11.410 --> 02:02:13.410
to learn of university
students silencing

02:02:13.410 --> 02:02:15.330
the opinions of others.

02:02:15.330 --> 02:02:18.340
He would have been even more
horrified that faculty members

02:02:18.340 --> 02:02:21.020
were often part of the
commencement censorship

02:02:21.020 --> 02:02:22.440
campaigns.

02:02:22.440 --> 02:02:25.890
For tenured professors,
to silence speakers

02:02:25.890 --> 02:02:28.220
whose views they
disagree with is really

02:02:28.220 --> 02:02:31.880
the height of hypocrisy,
especially when those protests

02:02:31.880 --> 02:02:34.200
happen in the
Northeast, the bastion

02:02:34.200 --> 02:02:36.290
of self-professed
liberal tolerance.

02:02:43.565 --> 02:02:47.030
Now, I'm glad to say
that Harvard has not

02:02:47.030 --> 02:02:52.870
caved into these commencement
censorship challenges.

02:02:52.870 --> 02:02:56.270
If it had, Colorado State
Senator Michael Johnston

02:02:56.270 --> 02:02:58.750
would not have had the chance
to address the Education

02:02:58.750 --> 02:03:00.300
School yesterday.

02:03:00.300 --> 02:03:02.580
Some students called
on the administration

02:03:02.580 --> 02:03:04.990
to rescind the
invitation to Johnston

02:03:04.990 --> 02:03:08.560
because they opposed some
of his education policies,

02:03:08.560 --> 02:03:12.190
but to their great credit,
President Faust and Dean Ryan

02:03:12.190 --> 02:03:13.520
stood firm.

02:03:13.520 --> 02:03:15.460
And as Dean Ryan
wrote to the students,

02:03:15.460 --> 02:03:18.800
quote, "I have encountered
many people of good faith

02:03:18.800 --> 02:03:23.230
who share my basic goals but
disagree with my views when

02:03:23.230 --> 02:03:26.830
it comes to the question of
how best to improve education.

02:03:26.830 --> 02:03:31.770
In my view, those differences
should be explored, debated,

02:03:31.770 --> 02:03:36.040
challenged, and questioned, but
they should also be respected

02:03:36.040 --> 02:03:38.100
and indeed celebrated."

02:03:38.100 --> 02:03:39.970
He could not have
been more correct.

02:03:39.970 --> 02:03:42.630
He could not have provided
a more valuable final lesson

02:03:42.630 --> 02:03:53.840
to the class of 2014.

02:03:53.840 --> 02:03:56.160
As a former chairman
at Johns Hopkins,

02:03:56.160 --> 02:03:59.620
I strongly believe that a
university's obligation is not

02:03:59.620 --> 02:04:03.210
to teach students what to
think but to teach students

02:04:03.210 --> 02:04:04.850
how to think.

02:04:04.850 --> 02:04:07.660
And that requires listening
to the other side,

02:04:07.660 --> 02:04:10.560
weighing arguments
without prejudicing them,

02:04:10.560 --> 02:04:12.925
and determining whether the
other side might actually

02:04:12.925 --> 02:04:15.490
have made some fair points.

02:04:15.490 --> 02:04:17.804
If the faculty fails
to do this, then it

02:04:17.804 --> 02:04:19.595
is the responsibility
of the administration

02:04:19.595 --> 02:04:23.170
and the governing body to step
in and make it a priority.

02:04:23.170 --> 02:04:26.780
If they do not-- if students
graduate with ears and minds

02:04:26.780 --> 02:04:29.140
closed, the
university has failed

02:04:29.140 --> 02:04:32.030
both the students and society.

02:04:32.030 --> 02:04:34.060
And if you want to
know where that leads,

02:04:34.060 --> 02:04:37.470
look no further
than Washington DC.

02:04:37.470 --> 02:04:42.130
Down in Washington, every major
question facing our country,

02:04:42.130 --> 02:04:46.160
involving our security, our
economy, our environment,

02:04:46.160 --> 02:04:48.110
and our health, is decided.

02:04:48.110 --> 02:04:50.560
Yet the two parties
decide those questions

02:04:50.560 --> 02:04:53.670
not by engaging with one
another but by trying

02:04:53.670 --> 02:04:57.140
to shout each other down
and by trying to repress

02:04:57.140 --> 02:05:01.550
and undermine the research
the counters their ideology.

02:05:01.550 --> 02:05:04.370
The more our universities
emulate that model,

02:05:04.370 --> 02:05:06.980
the worse off we
will be as a society.

02:05:06.980 --> 02:05:09.260
And let me give
you a few examples.

02:05:09.260 --> 02:05:11.820
For a decade, Congress
has barred the Centers

02:05:11.820 --> 02:05:13.560
for Disease Control
from conducting

02:05:13.560 --> 02:05:15.470
studies of gun violence.

02:05:15.470 --> 02:05:18.740
And recently Congress also
placed that prohibition

02:05:18.740 --> 02:05:21.400
on the National
Institute of Health.

02:05:21.400 --> 02:05:25.260
You have to ask yourself,
what are they afraid of?

02:05:25.260 --> 02:05:28.630
This year the Senate has delayed
a vote on President Obama's

02:05:28.630 --> 02:05:33.330
nominee for Surgeon General,
Dr. Vivek Murthy, a Harvard

02:05:33.330 --> 02:05:36.120
physician, because
he had the audacity

02:05:36.120 --> 02:05:38.560
to say that gun violence
is a public health

02:05:38.560 --> 02:05:40.650
crisis that should be tackled.

02:05:40.650 --> 02:05:41.800
Th gall of him.

02:05:50.958 --> 02:05:52.720
Let's get serious.

02:05:52.720 --> 02:05:57.660
When 86 Americans are killed
with guns every single day

02:05:57.660 --> 02:06:01.320
and shootings regularly occur
at our schools and universities,

02:06:01.320 --> 02:06:04.280
including last week's
tragedy at Santa Barbara,

02:06:04.280 --> 02:06:06.700
it would be almost
medical malpractice

02:06:06.700 --> 02:06:09.010
to say anything else.

02:06:09.010 --> 02:06:13.370
But in politics, as it is on
far too many college campuses,

02:06:13.370 --> 02:06:15.050
people don't listen
to facts that

02:06:15.050 --> 02:06:17.190
run counter to their ideology.

02:06:17.190 --> 02:06:18.430
They fear them.

02:06:18.430 --> 02:06:20.570
And nothing is more
frightening to them

02:06:20.570 --> 02:06:23.060
than scientific evidence.

02:06:23.060 --> 02:06:26.030
Earlier this year, the
state of South Carolina

02:06:26.030 --> 02:06:29.770
adopted new science standards
for its public schools,

02:06:29.770 --> 02:06:31.860
but the state
legislature blocked

02:06:31.860 --> 02:06:34.940
any mention of
natural selection.

02:06:34.940 --> 02:06:37.840
That is like teaching
economics without mentioning

02:06:37.840 --> 02:06:40.150
supply and demand.

02:06:40.150 --> 02:06:43.710
Once again, you have to ask,
what are they afraid of?

02:06:43.710 --> 02:06:45.880
And the answer, of
course, is obvious.

02:06:45.880 --> 02:06:47.850
Just as members of
Congress fear data

02:06:47.850 --> 02:06:50.860
that undermines their
ideological beliefs,

02:06:50.860 --> 02:06:53.940
these state legislators
feared scientific evidence

02:06:53.940 --> 02:06:56.640
that undermines their
religious beliefs.

02:06:56.640 --> 02:06:59.610
And if you want proof
of that, consider this.

02:06:59.610 --> 02:07:02.450
An eight-year-old
girl in South Carolina

02:07:02.450 --> 02:07:05.280
wrote to members of
the state legislature

02:07:05.280 --> 02:07:09.280
urging them to make the woolly
mammoth the official state

02:07:09.280 --> 02:07:10.830
fossil.

02:07:10.830 --> 02:07:13.800
Legislators thought
it was a great idea,

02:07:13.800 --> 02:07:16.830
because a woolly mammal fossil
was found in the state way

02:07:16.830 --> 02:07:19.870
back in 1725.

02:07:19.870 --> 02:07:21.810
But the state
Senate passed a bill

02:07:21.810 --> 02:07:24.410
defining the woolly
mammoth as having been,

02:07:24.410 --> 02:07:28.480
quote, "created on the sixth day
with the beasts of the field,"

02:07:28.480 --> 02:07:29.840
unquote.

02:07:29.840 --> 02:07:32.530
You can't make this stuff up.

02:07:32.530 --> 02:07:36.390
Here in 21st century
America, the wall

02:07:36.390 --> 02:07:39.460
between church and state
remains under attack,

02:07:39.460 --> 02:07:41.900
but it's up to all of us
to man the barricades.

02:07:51.150 --> 02:07:53.170
Unfortunately, the
same elected officials

02:07:53.170 --> 02:07:56.160
who put ideology and religion
over data and science

02:07:56.160 --> 02:07:58.960
when it comes to guns
and evolution, often

02:07:58.960 --> 02:08:02.180
are the most unwilling to accept
the scientific data on climate

02:08:02.180 --> 02:08:03.280
change.

02:08:03.280 --> 02:08:04.620
Now, don't get me wrong.

02:08:04.620 --> 02:08:07.376
Scientific skepticism
is healthy,

02:08:07.376 --> 02:08:08.750
but there's a
world of difference

02:08:08.750 --> 02:08:11.340
between scientific
skepticism that seeks out

02:08:11.340 --> 02:08:16.390
more evidence and ideological
stubbornness that shuts it out.

02:08:16.390 --> 02:08:18.980
Given the general attitude
of many elected officials

02:08:18.980 --> 02:08:22.020
toward science, it's no wonder
the federal government has

02:08:22.020 --> 02:08:24.700
abdicated its
responsibility to invest

02:08:24.700 --> 02:08:27.080
in scientific
research, much of which

02:08:27.080 --> 02:08:29.520
occurs at our universities.

02:08:29.520 --> 02:08:32.050
Today federal spending on
research and development

02:08:32.050 --> 02:08:34.970
as a percentage of
GNP is lower than it

02:08:34.970 --> 02:08:37.590
has been in more
than 50 years, which

02:08:37.590 --> 02:08:40.010
is allowing the rest of the
world to catch up and even

02:08:40.010 --> 02:08:42.860
surpass the US in
scientific research.

02:08:42.860 --> 02:08:45.280
The federal government
is flunking science,

02:08:45.280 --> 02:08:47.900
just as many state
governments are.

02:08:47.900 --> 02:08:49.610
But we must not
become a country that

02:08:49.610 --> 02:08:53.600
turns its back on
science or on each other.

02:08:53.600 --> 02:08:56.250
Now, I get back to
the class of 2014.

02:08:56.250 --> 02:08:59.130
You graduates must
help lead the way.

02:08:59.130 --> 02:09:03.200
On every issue, we must follow
the evidence where it leads

02:09:03.200 --> 02:09:05.445
and listen to people
where they are.

02:09:08.480 --> 02:09:11.950
If we do that, there is no
problem we cannot solve,

02:09:11.950 --> 02:09:16.820
no gridlock we cannot break,
no compromise we cannot broker.

02:09:16.820 --> 02:09:21.500
The more we exchange or embrace
a free exchange of ideas,

02:09:21.500 --> 02:09:24.290
and the more we accept
that political diversity,

02:09:24.290 --> 02:09:28.410
the healthy we are, the
stronger our society will be.

02:09:28.410 --> 02:09:31.110
Now, I know this has not been
a traditional commencement

02:09:31.110 --> 02:09:32.340
speech.

02:09:32.340 --> 02:09:35.920
And in fact, it may keep me from
passing a dissertation defense

02:09:35.920 --> 02:09:40.700
in the humanities department,
but there is no easy time

02:09:40.700 --> 02:09:42.820
to say hard things.

02:09:42.820 --> 02:09:44.950
Graduates, throughout
your lives,

02:09:44.950 --> 02:09:48.180
do not be afraid of saying
what you believe is right,

02:09:48.180 --> 02:09:50.960
no matter how
unpopular it may be,

02:09:50.960 --> 02:09:55.080
especially when it comes to
defending the rights of others.

02:09:55.080 --> 02:09:58.180
Stand up for the rights of
others, and in some ways

02:09:58.180 --> 02:10:00.095
it's even more important
than standing up

02:10:00.095 --> 02:10:02.450
for your own
rights, because when

02:10:02.450 --> 02:10:05.850
people seek to repress
freedom for some

02:10:05.850 --> 02:10:08.470
and you may remain
silent, you are

02:10:08.470 --> 02:10:14.390
complicit in that repression and
you may well become its victim.

02:10:14.390 --> 02:10:16.110
Do not be complicit.

02:10:16.110 --> 02:10:17.900
Do not follow the crowd.

02:10:17.900 --> 02:10:19.593
Speak up and fight back.

02:10:19.593 --> 02:10:21.540
You will take your lumps.

02:10:21.540 --> 02:10:23.170
I can assure you of that.

02:10:23.170 --> 02:10:25.910
You will lose some friends
and make some enemies.

02:10:25.910 --> 02:10:28.410
I can assure you of that, too.

02:10:28.410 --> 02:10:31.530
But the arc of history
will be on your side,

02:10:31.530 --> 02:10:34.290
and our nation will
be stronger for it.

02:10:34.290 --> 02:10:37.950
Now, all of you graduates have
earned today's celebration.

02:10:37.950 --> 02:10:41.440
You have a lot to be proud
of, a lot to be grateful for.

02:10:41.440 --> 02:10:44.760
So tonight, as you leave
this great university behind,

02:10:44.760 --> 02:10:47.565
have one last scorpion
bowl at the Kong.

02:10:47.565 --> 02:10:49.600
On second thought, don't.

02:10:49.600 --> 02:10:52.540
And tomorrow get
back to work making

02:10:52.540 --> 02:10:57.080
our country and our world freer
forever, freer for everyone.

02:10:57.080 --> 02:10:58.100
God bless and good luck.

02:11:41.370 --> 02:11:44.230
Thank you, Mr.
Bloomberg, for delivering

02:11:44.230 --> 02:11:48.460
such thoughtful remarks
to our community.

02:11:48.460 --> 02:11:53.920
As we prepare to close
these afternoon exercises,

02:11:53.920 --> 02:11:57.690
please stand once again
and join me now as we

02:11:57.690 --> 02:12:01.290
sing our alma mater,
"Fair Harvard."

02:12:01.290 --> 02:12:03.175
The words are in your program.

02:14:41.760 --> 02:14:46.620
On behalf of the Harvard
Alumni Association,

02:14:46.620 --> 02:14:53.090
let me once again welcome and
congratulate the class of 2014.

02:14:53.090 --> 02:14:58.620
You join one of the world's most
respected alumni communities,

02:14:58.620 --> 02:15:02.080
and we welcome you.

02:15:02.080 --> 02:15:10.890
I now hereby declare the 2014
meeting of the Harvard Alumni

02:15:10.890 --> 02:15:15.420
Association adjourned,
to reconvene

02:15:15.420 --> 02:15:21.430
same time, same
place, same weather,

02:15:21.430 --> 02:15:26.704
on the 28th of May, 2015.

02:15:26.704 --> 02:15:28.195
Thank you for coming.

02:15:44.099 --> 02:15:48.816
And here we are at the
close of the 145th meeting

02:15:48.816 --> 02:15:52.740
of the Harvard Alumni
Association in conclusion

02:15:52.740 --> 02:15:54.076
to Harvard's 363rd commencement.

02:15:56.860 --> 02:16:03.418
We heard former mayor of New
York City Michael Bloomberg

02:16:03.418 --> 02:16:10.980
charge the class of 2014 to
follow evidence where it leads.

02:16:10.980 --> 02:16:13.670
It was an appeal for the
preservation of freedom

02:16:13.670 --> 02:16:17.745
of expression, not only
on college campuses

02:16:17.745 --> 02:16:21.885
but in cities and in towns
throughout our democracy.

02:16:24.420 --> 02:16:27.850
Mayor Bloomberg said that
freedom of expression

02:16:27.850 --> 02:16:31.440
and tolerance are the
hallmarks of a democracy

02:16:31.440 --> 02:16:34.950
and that too often
on college campuses

02:16:34.950 --> 02:16:38.660
liberals were repressing
conservative ideas

02:16:38.660 --> 02:16:43.270
and not allowing
expression for those ideas.

02:16:43.270 --> 02:16:47.080
He's concerned that today
with liberals repressing

02:16:47.080 --> 02:16:49.660
conservatives similar
to the McCarthy era

02:16:49.660 --> 02:16:53.040
when right wings were
repressing liberals.

02:16:53.040 --> 02:16:55.469
He said it's the responsibility
of the university

02:16:55.469 --> 02:17:00.100
to teach students how to think,
to listen to the other side,

02:17:00.100 --> 02:17:02.871
and to be able to discuss,
debate, and learn.

02:17:05.580 --> 02:17:08.219
This was the charge
of Michael Bloomberg

02:17:08.219 --> 02:17:12.309
to the Harvard class of 2014.

02:17:12.309 --> 02:17:14.007
Rennie.

02:17:14.007 --> 02:17:17.680
Our president first
noted the buildings

02:17:17.680 --> 02:17:21.162
around the theater,
which contribute

02:17:21.162 --> 02:17:23.780
to the support of our students.

02:17:23.780 --> 02:17:25.889
She then outlined
the obligations

02:17:25.889 --> 02:17:28.850
which Harvard shared purposes.

02:17:28.850 --> 02:17:31.363
Our research efforts, she noted.

02:17:31.363 --> 02:17:35.862
We owe the world our research
efforts and entrepreneurship.

02:17:35.862 --> 02:17:39.580
We owe the world to produce
the knowledge and education

02:17:39.580 --> 02:17:40.927
of question.

02:17:40.927 --> 02:17:43.619
And we owe the world to
create critical questions

02:17:43.619 --> 02:17:46.320
whose answers will
shape the future.

02:17:46.320 --> 02:17:49.495
And finally, we owe the
future men and women

02:17:49.495 --> 02:17:51.980
to be teachers and
public servants,

02:17:51.980 --> 02:17:54.340
ready to take on
today's problems

02:17:54.340 --> 02:17:58.780
and continue to invest
in them in the future.

02:17:58.780 --> 02:18:02.420
Thank you for joining us
for the afternoon exercises

02:18:02.420 --> 02:18:05.840
of Harvard's 363th commencement.

02:18:05.840 --> 02:18:08.760
And I will conclude
with the "Villanelle

02:18:08.760 --> 02:18:13.629
for an Anniversary," written
for Harvard's 350th celebration

02:18:13.629 --> 02:18:16.730
in 1986 by Seamus Heaney.

02:18:16.730 --> 02:18:21.860
He entitled the Villanelle
"John Harvard Walks the Yard."

02:18:21.860 --> 02:18:23.400
"A spirit moved.

02:18:23.400 --> 02:18:25.709
John Harvard walked the yard.

02:18:25.709 --> 02:18:30.495
The atom lay unsplit, the west
unwon, the books stood opened

02:18:30.495 --> 02:18:33.020
and the gates unbarred.

02:18:33.020 --> 02:18:36.059
The maps dreamt
on like moondust.

02:18:36.059 --> 02:18:37.530
Nothing stirred.

02:18:37.530 --> 02:18:40.500
The future was a
verb in hibernation.

02:18:40.500 --> 02:18:41.850
A spirit moved.

02:18:41.850 --> 02:18:44.139
John Harvard walked the yard.

02:18:44.139 --> 02:18:47.940
Before the classic style,
before the clapboard,

02:18:47.940 --> 02:18:51.700
all through the small hours of
an origin, the books stood open

02:18:51.700 --> 02:18:54.090
and the gate unbarred.

02:18:54.090 --> 02:18:57.070
Night passage of
a migratory bird.

02:18:57.070 --> 02:18:58.480
Wingflap.

02:18:58.480 --> 02:18:59.950
Gownflap.

02:18:59.950 --> 02:19:02.540
Like a homing pigeon,
a spirit moved.

02:19:02.540 --> 02:19:05.030
John Harvard walked the yard.

02:19:05.030 --> 02:19:12.540
Was that his soul, look, sped
to its reward by grace or works?

02:19:12.540 --> 02:19:13.719
A shooting star?

02:19:13.719 --> 02:19:14.760
An omen?

02:19:14.760 --> 02:19:18.090
The books stood open
and the gate unbarred.

02:19:18.090 --> 02:19:22.059
Begin again where frosts
and tests were hard.

02:19:22.059 --> 02:19:23.920
Find yourself or founder.

02:19:23.920 --> 02:19:26.480
Here, imagine, a spirit moves.

02:19:26.480 --> 02:19:28.700
John Harvard walked the yard.

02:19:28.700 --> 02:19:32.590
The books stand open
and the gates unbarred."

02:19:32.590 --> 02:19:34.620
Thank you so much,
and we look forward

02:19:34.620 --> 02:19:41.370
to seeing you on May 28,
2015 for the 146th meeting

02:19:41.370 --> 02:19:43.260
of the Harvard
Alumni Association

02:19:43.260 --> 02:19:46.120
as part of Harvard's
364th commencement.

